Golfer Langer Receives the Sports Pyramid
His experience on the horse is clear .
At the end of a golf tournament in South Africa Bernhard Langer and some colleagues were looking for a change with a horse ride on the beach .
It was a first for the 58 @-@ year @-@ old .
CHIO : &quot; Golden Sports Pyramid &quot; for Bernhard Langer
After a few minutes , the horses remembered their evening at work , chasing home at a fast gallop to the feeding troughs .
One kilometre at this pace , I was afraid .
&quot; It was not a good experience , &quot; Langer says .
And with that the riding career ended again .
On Saturday , Germany &apos;s best golfer of all time - 101 tournament victories - was once again near horses .
He and his family were guided over the grounds of the ALRV , and he did not even swing on a horse for photo purposes .
Langer was in Aachen for the first time and therefore also at the CHIO .
The reason was quite convincing .
The German sports aid presented the man from Anhausen with the Golden Sports Pyramid in the form of a small gala .
There is no shortage of awards for the likeable athlete .
Federal Cross of Merit , Silver Laurel Leaf , Champions Tour Player of the Year ...
Even the British Queen has already reproached him .
Langer is the 18th winner of the sports pyramid .
On Saturday , he met the first prize winner , Hans Günter Winkler , in Aachen .
&quot; This award means a lot to me , &quot; says Langer , &quot; because it is awarded not only for sporting success , but also for social commitment . &quot;
Langer has been supporting young talent for decades .
And so he immediately passed on the prize money of 25,000 euros .
With 15 other outstanding athletes , the double US champion was admitted on Saturday to the &quot; Hall of Fame of German Sports . &quot;
The winners are the track and field champions Hartwig Gauder and Harald Schmitt , the Torner Eberhard Gienger , the fenders Cornelia Hanisch , Alexander Pusch and Arnd Schmitt , the rower Peter @-@ Michael Kolbe , Bob driver Meinhard Nehmer , the judoka Frank Wieneke , the jumper Alwin Shockemöhle and posthumously the handball player Erhard Wunderlich .
Many of these sports legends had come to Aachen on Saturday .
After the official part , the illustrious company moved to the Springstadion , where the Lavazza Prize was awarded .
Bernhard Langer kept distance from the big animals .
Clinton and Trump &apos;s Economic Policy Compared : It &apos;s all about the money
Investing in infrastructure and preventing the TTP trade deal - that is what both Clinton and Trump want .
However , the two US presidential candidates are divided on tax and energy policy and on a fundamental issue .
Underlying the differences in economic policy between Donald Trump and Hillary Clinton is a fundamental , rather philosophical difference .
The , about the role of the state .
Trump wants to keep them rather small when in doubt , and warns about how government can harm the economy - with taxes and regulations .
Clinton wants to tax the economy to death and regulate it to death , he says .
He himself would be very different , Trump claims .
He will roll back regulations massively , and he will push for far @-@ reaching tax reform , with lower tax rates - for individuals and for businesses .
Clinton , on the other hand , says that the state has certain tasks to perform , that it has opportunities for the disadvantaged and needs money to do so .
That is why taxes on the rich would be raised , she says .
Interestingly , both are very close on the subject of infrastructure .
Trump and Clinton say that we need to invest in them almost word for word .
The Democratic candidate even announces the biggest investment in new jobs since the Second World War .
Government infrastructure investment programs are classic democratic policies , and are strongly opposed by , say , the Republicans &quot; anti @-@ state Tea Party wing .
So Trump may yet face intra @-@ party discussions .
The differences in energy and climate policy are more striking .
Trump wants to build coal @-@ fired power plants and restart coal production in the US .
Oil production is also to be possible in previously protected areas , and he wants to terminate the Paris agreement on climate change .
Clinton , by contrast , explicitly wants to expand renewable energy with her investment program , calling for , &quot; One country will become the clean energy superpower and create millions of jobs . &quot;
&quot; It will probably be either China , Germany or America - I want us to be . &quot;
But not only in infrastructure , but also in international trade agreements , the two competitors are not too far apart .
TPP , the Trans @-@ Pacific Trade Agreement , does not want to sign either .
At the same time , they do not want to isolate the US from international trade - but simply to protect American jobs better .
Clinton , for example , is calling for them to be better paid .
The current minimum wage of $ 7.25 is a pittance .
She wants to raise it to $ 15 an hour .
What Trump wants to do on this issue is not entirely clear : first he says the minimum wage must go up , then he says it must not be changed .
But the big discussion in the coming months is more likely to revolve around the two camps &quot; tax policies .
On one side stands Trump , who wants to ease the burden on business and citizens in order to boost growth .
His critics reproach him for only increasing the budget deficit .
On the other side stands Clinton , who wants at least the rich to pay more taxes and whose critics say : more taxes are not the answer , either .
Escape : &apos; Every woman who has fled has experience of sexual violence &apos; .
Sexual violence is almost a part of everyday life for women fleeing on their own .
When they arrive in Germany , they are often traumatized .
A house offers refuge .
Four women sit in a large kitchen .
Each has a baby of at most one year old .
One put her little son in her arms .
He takes a curious look at the room with large eyes .
His mother gazes at the table top .
Until she realizes that she is being watched .
She smile briefly and kisses the little one .
The scene appears normal .
Until you talk to Katrin Bahr .
She is chief executive officer of Condrobs , a social assistance provider in Bavaria , and deals , among other things , with the issue of women on the run .
The four women in the kitchen are poultry .
They live in the north of Munich in one of the few decentralized accommodation facilities for single women and their children in Bavaria .
In January , Condrobs opened the facility together with Pro Familia and Munich &apos;s Women &apos;s Relief .
It has just been officially opened .
60 people live there - about 40 women and 20 children .
There are no men - not even as visitors .
The exception is a guard on the doorstep .
&quot; It is no exaggeration to say that every woman who arrives here has had experiences of sexual violence in her flight , &quot; says Bahr .
&quot; Men are fleeing wars because of political persecution , because they are threatened with torture or death , or because their families send them to Europe as bearers of hope , &quot; she says .
In the case of women , other reasons for flight predominate : &quot; Many steal from them secretly because they see no other way out . &quot;
In their homeland , they have experienced sexual violence , forced marriages , honour killings , slavery or forced prostitution .
That is what drives them on .
On the run that continues .
&quot; It is not uncommon for smugglers to demand a sexual act for a bottle of water , for example , &quot; says Bahr .
And women are alone , they are not protected by their families .
Who thinks that the end is wrong as soon as they arrive in Germany , tells Bahr .
Here , too , single women in refugee camps would often be seen as inferior and , at worst , abused .
As a result , about 90 % of women living in the housing in the north of Munich are traumatised , she estimates .
&quot; Some of the children were certainly not born voluntarily . &quot;
Many women are so used to saying nothing .
&quot; Or they dare not speak openly about what happened , because the shame is too great . &quot;
Since they often couldn &apos;t help each other , they need more accommodation just for them , Bahr demands .
In Bavaria , the seven district governments are responsible for housing refugees .
When asked whether they knew of a project in their area of competence similar to the one in Munich , some say no .
In the Upper Palatinate and Upper Franconia , for example , there is no such thing in government accommodation .
According to Karl @-@ Heinz Meyer , press spokesman for the government , women who have fled alone are not accommodated separately in Swabia either .
In Upper Bavaria , Lower Franconia and Central Franconia , there are some shared accommodation floors or houses only for single women and their children .
The exception is Lower Bavaria , where there are two central lodgings exclusively for women .
The Committee on Women &apos;s Rights and Gender Equality in the European Parliament is also calling for women to be placed separately from men .
A study published for the committee said : &apos; It is very important that men and women are accommodated separately &apos; .
&apos;If there is no privacy , or if men and women are accommodated together , violence against women can occur - on an ongoing basis . &apos;
The study states that washrooms in particular should be separate and easily accessible to women .
The extent to which women feel this need for protection can be seen from the rush to the house in Munich .
&quot; We have had a long waiting list ever since the rumour spread that we have it , &quot; says Bahr .
It would be easy to open a second house .
Assistant doctors strike : demands for new industrial action
Deputy junior doctors have called on their union to approve new industrial action in their disputes over a new contract .
The Junior Doctors Committee ( JDC ) of the British Medical Association ( BMA ) has called on its entire council to approve more industrial action measures from the beginning of September .
The JDC said that ministers had failed to address concerns about the treaty .
Assistant doctors and medical students voted in July to reject a contract that was agreed with the BMA .
It was rejected by 58 % of its members who voted in the elections .
In a letter to members published on Twitter on Thursday evening , JDC Chairman Ellen McCourt said that the government had remained &quot; tenaciously quiet &quot; about problems , causing the treaty to be rejected .
She said : &apos; In view of this , the JDC Board has voted to reject the proposed new treaty outright and has called for official renegotiations on all your concerns . &apos;
In response to the government &apos;s silence , the JDC Board of Directors has today formally requested a special meeting of the BMA Council to approve an ongoing program of escalating industrial action , beginning in early September .
The disputes caused junior doctors to strike six times this year , the first total loss in the history of the NHS .
Dr. Johann Malawana , Head of the BMA Assistant Doctors , resigned after the election to reject the agreed contract terms recommended by the BMA .
He informed BMA members during the sessions prior to the vote by 54,000 junior doctors and medical students that the contract was beneficial and should be adopted .
After the vote , Health Minister Jeremy Hunt said that the contract would be enforced on doctors in England .
Russia and Turkey : An &quot; Alliance of Outsiders &quot; ?
It was a gesture that ended a crisis .
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce an official end to the eight @-@ month war of words and economic sanctions .
But when Vladimir Putin receives his Turkish counterpart in the gold @-@ plated hall of the St. Petersburg Palace , I cannot help thinking that Ankara wants this reconciliation the most .
There was the handshake , yes .
But Putin &apos;s smile looked narrow , and he radiated little warmth , even for his modest circumstances .
Recep Tayyip Erdogan , on the other hand , spoke repeatedly of his &quot; dear friend &quot; Putin - as many as five times , according to one report .
I couldn &apos;t count it anymore .
He also promised that relations with Russia would not only return to their pre @-@ crisis levels , but will even improve .
The next day , a newspaper wrote that Erdogan had behaved as if nothing bad had ever happened .
Rather , his enthusiasm seemed to me to suggest the opposite .
But a sustainable chill radiating from Putin showed that Russia &apos;s leader had forgotten nothing .
Indeed , the cause of the crisis was the first he mentioned in his opening remarks : Turkey &apos;s downing of a Russian warplane on Syria &apos;s border .
Moscow &apos;s reaction at the time was furious .
Putin parted out and accused Ankara of stabbing Russia in the back .
The offence was even greater because it was committed by a supposed friend .
Rebuilding trust will be difficult , if not impossible .
Russian public opinion has changed since November .
For months , the state @-@ controlled media carried out a vigorous , unrestricted attack on Ankara .
All of a sudden , it seemed that the Turks were responsible for everything .
Most seriously , senior officials have accused Erdogan &apos;s own family of benefiting from the illegal oil trade in areas of Syria controlled by the Islamic State .
He has vigorously denied this .
But in St Petersburg , the official message was that it was time to look forward .
After all , this meeting took place only because President Erdogan offered Putin the apology he wanted to hear .
Russia has achieved a kind of victory .
For Ankara , the benefits of a cease @-@ fire are clear .
Erdogan needs , first and foremost , all the friends he can get after he was almost impeached in a failed coup last month .
He has also been shocked by repeated terrorist attacks on Turkey .
But there are also economic motives .
Russian sanctions have hit Turkey hard - in particular , the ban on charter flights , which typically bring several million Russian tourists to the Turkish coast each year .
The number has fallen by almost 90 % .
In Russia , tour operators and charter companies will be made easier when flights resume .
They are counting on a late @-@ season rush to the Mediterranean .
State television this week predicted cheaper fruit and vegetables once Turkish agricultural imports are allowed again .
As one report in Vedemosti put it , &apos; tourists there long , tomatoes here long &apos; .
But the visit had an additional political value for Moscow .
Ankara is angry with the West because it sees its response to the attempted takeover as a weak response .
Add to that persistent resentment at the snail &apos;s pace of EU accession negotiations , and Putin - eager to take advantage of the cool mood and downgrade Turkey &apos;s relationship with the West .
The Russian leader certainly won a bonus in Ankara for calling for support for the elected authorities after the attempted coup .
This goes without saying in Moscow , which itself is deeply afraid of regime change .
The summit meeting in this shining palace by the sea allowed Russia and Turkey to portray what one analyst once described to me as an &quot; alliance of outsiders &quot; : two countries that feel alienated by the West , badly treated , and now allied .
However , despite the public reconciliation , there are still major differences between the two .
The biggest difference is Syria , where Moscow recently gave itself the role of peacemaker , but where Russia and Turkey support opposing sides .
It could be significant that , after almost three hours of initial talks , both presidents said at the press conference that they had not even touched on the issue .
Turkey &apos;s president deliberately avoided answering a question about their differences , while Putin chose to emphasize them .
There is no clear consensus on where to find common ground on Syria .
But , after months of outright hostilities - and given the potential for complete disaster when NATO member Turkey shot down the Russian jet - it is surely better that the two leaders at least talk to each other again .
Royal Bank of Scotland no longer available to customers outside Scotland
According to the CEO of the Bank , the RBS brand is to be reduced to a back @-@ office role .
The Royal Bank of Scotland will no longer be available to customers outside Scotland .
Ross McEwan told BBC Scotland that the RBS brand was linked to the bank &apos;s global ambitions .
The Bank has distanced itself ever since , when it nearly collapsed and had to be rescued eight years ago .
During this time , brand strategists have used &quot; RBS &quot; to protect other consumer financial brands .
She sponsored international sport with millions of pounds , from Six Nations Rugby to Wimbledon winner Andy Murray .
But now it has decided to focus on more national brands .
The Royal Bank of Scotland will be available only to customers in Scotland , but will not be initialised .
In England and Wales , all RSB references , headquarters and stock exchange listing will change to NatWest .
The Ulster Bank brand is already used for customers in the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland .
There are other , smaller retail brands that will become more important - Coutts , Adam &amp; Co , Drummond and Holt &apos;s Military Bank .
McEwan was interviewed by customers and employees during a tour in Inverness @-@ shire .
He told BBC Scotland : &quot; The RSB brand will become our investor brand and the brand under which our employees will be employed , as we will now become more of a trademark bank . &quot;
When the bank itself became a global brand , RBS became a global brand .
What I am saying now is that we are not pursuing global goals , but local ones .
Each of these brands will stand for something completely different in their own communities and our employees will work with customers under these brands .
RBS has already stated that it will no longer continue its Six Nations sponsorship and that it will increase the visibility of the various brands in its sports sponsorship .
&quot; It is time for us to become the bank of brands , because how do we focus internally ( we have asked ) on making this a better bank for customers ? &quot; said the CEO .
It would have been very cynical three years ago if we had said that we were going to be a great bank for our customers and we had launched these brands .
But with our work , our focus on customer needs and not our own , I think many changes will be seen .
We can relaunch these brands , so I think the time has come .
Frankie Dettori achieves on Predilection his 3,000 profit at Newmarket .
Dettori sprays champagne after a double at Newmarket , which brings him 3,000 profit .
Jockey Frankie Dettori secured his 3,000 British win at Newmarket on Friday .
He set a milestone on Predilection , which is trained by John Gosden , on his local circuit with his second win of the night .
The 45 @-@ year @-@ old Italian is the sixth jockey to reach the milestone in the flat race .
He will be succeeded by Sir Gordon Richards , Doug Smith , Lester Piggott , Pat Eddry and Willie Carson .
The three @-@ time winner , Dettori , who previously won on Ghayyar , said , &quot; It &apos;s something special . &quot;
I am very emotional because my family is here as well .
I am very happy that it happened at Newmarket because I arrived here 30 years ago .
It is not a big meeting , it is not Royal Ascot - it is a banal Friday evening with 20,000 people .
I am relief and very modest .
Dettori takes up the rejoicing when he wins on Predilection .
Two jockeys have reached the milestone in the obstacle race - Jockey Richard Johnson and retired 20 @-@ time winner Sir Anthony McCoy , who scored more than 4,300 wins in a record @-@ breaking career .
Lester Piggott , the nine @-@ time Derby winner , had 4,493 career wins .
Frankie is one of the best jockey of modern times and it is no surprise that he has reached this milestone , which few before him have reached .
He has style and strength , but it is his tactical intellect that sets him apart from the others in the weight control room .
He is a fantastic ambassador for races , his enthusiasm and charisma has been inspiring fans for years for this sport .
I said to Frankie a couple of weeks ago at Epsom that he would have won 6,000 if he had not just been a weekend and major tournament jockey !
Frankie has been riding winners in the UK for almost 30 years , which is great .
He has a lively personality , which is good for a British race , but beyond that he is an incredible jockey .
Frankie Dettori celebrated the milestone with a typical Flying Dismount .
From Flying Finishes to Flying Dismounts , Frankie Dettori has been the flagship of British flat racing for two decades .
It was nervous .
A whole series of major tournament wins , including his famous &quot; Glorious Seven &quot; in Ascot in 1996 , but he also survived a plane crash and was banned from drugs .
Three years ago , he was initially struggling when he returned from his six @-@ month suspension , but he showed an impressive characteristic strength to defy his doubters and return to his best form .
And he &apos;s far from over - Dettori once said that he wants to continue in competitions until he &apos;s at least 50 years old .
Russia &apos;s Putin fires Chief of Staff Sergei Ivanov
Russian President Vladimir Putin has unexpectedly fired his chief of staff , Sergei Ivanov .
For many years , Ivanov was part of Putin &apos;s closest circle of trust .
The 63 @-@ year @-@ old has been appointed Special Representative for Environmental and Transport Affairs .
According to a Kremlin statement , Putin has &quot; ordered Ivanov &apos;s release from his duties as head of Russia &apos;s presidential administration , without giving any reason . &quot;
Anton Vaino , who has been Ivanov &apos;s deputy since 2012 , has been appointed his successor .
Vaino , 44 , is a former diplomat .
Born in the Estonian capital Tallinn in 1972 , he graduated from the prestigious Moscow State Institute for International Relations ( MGIMO ) and worked in the Embassy in Tokyo .
The Kremlin &apos;s Web site says ( in Russian ) that he was later chief of protocol and chief of staff of the administration .
About his appointment , he said to Putin : &quot; Thank you for your trust . &quot;
I think that the most important task of the government is to support your work as Head of State on draft laws and controls to implement your instructions .
Putin told the Russian TV station on Friday that Ivanov had asked to leave his post and had recommended Vaino as his successor .
Are the smiling faces convincing ?
That move has shrouded Moscow in secrecy .
Sergei Ivanov has long been one of Vladimir Putin &apos;s closest confidants and , like him , works for the Soviet secret service , the KGB .
As chief of staff , he was one of the country &apos;s most powerful men .
In a televised meeting with President Putin , both men claimed that the chief of staff resigned at his own request .
But , despite the smile on the cameras , few here are convinced - especially now , just before the general election .
So is this the result of some kind of power struggle ?
Nobody knows that at the moment .
But the official claim - that a man once touted as a potential president would suddenly want to guide Russian environmental policy - was met with great skepticism .
In his remarks to Putin , quoted on the Kremlin &apos;s Web site , Ivanov said , &quot; It is true that in early 2012 , in a conversation , I asked you to entrust me with this very complicated post - one might almost say - for four years .
As it turns out , I have been chairman of Russia &apos;s presidential administration for four years and eight months .
Ivanov accepted the post in December 2011 .
He was previously Deputy Prime Minister and Defence Minister .
He is a member of Russia &apos;s Security Council and , like Putin , a former member of the KGB State Security Service .
In the late 1990 &quot; s , when Putin was chairman of the Federal Security Service ( FSB ) , which replaced the KGB , Ivanov was appointed as his proxy .
When Putin came to power , he named Ivanov as one of five people he trusted the most .
It was once thought that Ivanov might become President of Russia after Putin &apos;s second term , because a third Putin term would have violated the constitution .
But that post was taken by another of Putin &apos;s close allies , Dmitry Medvedev .
Putin became Prime Minister before he became President again three and a half years later .
