The £ 2 per day drug that can reduce heart attack risk .
Thousands of heart attack patients will benefit from a £ 2 per day drug after authorities have recommended that more people be given it for a longer period of time .
Ticagrelor , a anticoagulant medication , reduces the risk of repeated heart attacks in people with heart disease .
The drug is administered as early as 12 months after a heart attack , reducing the risk of stroke or another heart attack .
The NICE regulatory agency has recommended taking this medicine for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular problems .
The NICE regulatory agency has recommended taking this medicine for four years to further reduce the risk of cardiovascular problems .
Around 140,000 people suffer a heart attack each year , and a quarter of them suffer another heart attack or stroke .
Heart attacks and strokes are caused by accumulations of greasy materials in the arterial walls that form coatings .
If the plaque breaks apart , it can cause a blood clots that clog the blood flow to the heart , causing heart attacks .
When the blood clots dissolve , they can flow through the bloodstream and clog up the flow of blood to the brain , causing a stroke .
People who have already had a heart attack are at higher risk of having another .
Ticagrelor , manufactured by the British company AstraZeneca and marketed under the trade name Brilique , reduces this risk by making the formation of blood clots less likely .
NICE &apos;s draft guidelines , published today , recommend taking 90mg of Ticagrelor for 12 months , followed by 60mg of aspirin twice a day for the next three years .
Professor Carole Longson , director of the NICE Health Technology Assessment Centre , said : &apos; Despite the availability of secondary prevention , a quarter of all people who have suffered a heart attack have another heart attack or stroke - often with disastrous consequences . &apos;
Fears of another heart attack can have a significant negative impact on a person &apos;s quality of life .
Experience shows that Ticagrelor , in combination with aspirin , is effective in reducing further heart attacks and strokes in people who have already had a heart attack .
Through a preliminary recommendation from Ticagrelor , we are pleased that we are able to expand available treatment options to thousands of people who can benefit from them .
Information on the effectiveness and safety of Ticagrelor - in particular , bleeding risk - is limited to a period of up to three years , and the draft bond does not recommend treatment beyond that period .
A Culture of Political Correctness Blooms Electoral Fraud in Muslim Areas
Former mayor of Tower Hamlets Lutfur Rahman was removed from office last year on a government report of corruption .
A culture of political correctness has led to widespread electoral fraud in Muslim communities being deliberately ignored , as a devastating government report revealed today .
Former cabinet member Sir Eric Pickles is verbally attacking the police , election observers and town halls for ignoring evidence of electoral abuse due to &quot; over @-@ sensitivity to ethnicity and religion . &quot;
The former Minister for Integration and Local Government , who is now an anti @-@ corruption king , said that intimidating voters for religious reasons would be so bad that the police should be allowed to set up barricades outside polling booths to protect intimidated voters .
It recommends that voters should have an identity card with them in order to prove their identity in elections .
At present , all a voter has to do is give his name and address .
The report proposes that inks that cannot be removed should be put on a person &apos;s finger when they cast their votes , in order to prevent someone voting twice .
Whistleblowers should be given more protection , says Sir Eric .
It calls for the press to have more access to community documents and decisions by non @-@ official committees or working groups .
&quot; This serves not only against electoral fraud , but also to protect local government from the broader culture of corruption and financial fraud that accompanies it , &quot; he said .
The report was ordered by Downing Street as a result of the Tower Hamlet electoral scandal in eastern London .
Last year , a special election court ruled that acting mayor Lutfur Rahman should be removed from office after a litany of corrupt and illegal practices .
The court found that Rahman had &quot; cynically perverted the religious feelings of his Muslim community , &quot; and that he had silenced his critics with accusations of racism and Islamophobia .
Rahman is said to have conducted his campaign &quot; on the basis that it is the religious duty of Muslims to elect him . &quot;
Up to 300 votes were either doubtful or the result of imitation in which one person votes as someone else .
Sir Eric said there is evidence of fraud across the country .
He was particularly alarmist about fraudulent postal voting - in which older members of the Muslim community had put pressure on people to elect a candidate of their choice .
Sir Eric , pictured , made several recommendations to clean up the electoral system , including holding identity cards to prove identity .
His report states : &apos; As proof , pressure has been brought to bear on vulnerable members of some ethnic minorities , particularly women and young people , to vote in accordance with the will of the elderly , particularly communities with Pakistani or Bangladeshi backgrounds .
&quot; There were concerns that ... state institutions had knowingly ignored such behavior due to &quot; politically correct &quot; over @-@ sensitivity to ethnicity and religion . &quot;
Sir Eric made 50 recommendations to clean up the system , including a ban on political activists processing ballot papers to stop &quot; election harvests . &quot;
The report under consideration by Theresa May also calls for stricter registration checks to prevent the electoral register from being used for immigration and social fraud .
Consider asking voters for your ID before the election .
Use non @-@ removable ink on a person &apos;s finger once they have cast their vote to prevent someone from voting twice .
To carry out systematic checks on a person &apos;s nationality to ensure that they are eligible to vote .
A three @-@ year restriction on applications for automatic postal voting .
Prohibition on political activists processing complete postal votes and envelopes of postal votes .
Give the police the power to set up barriers around election stations .
A legislative amendment to facilitate charges of intimidation under the Representation of the People Act 1983 .
Prohibition of photography in election stations .
Requirement that only English be used in polling stations ( with the exception of Wales ) .
Increased training to ensure that employees enforce the rule that voters go into the polling booth alone .
