The idea of licking the sink of a train toilet , which has already been used by thousands of others , may be utterly repellent , but there are in fact more bad bacteria in a kitchen sink .
On his trip around Europe , Mr Wright talked to doctors and medical professionals about the promotion of intestinal bacteria and his own health .
Fortunately , nothing he licked left more than a bad aftertaste in his mouth .
Mr Wright became famous for testing the resilience of his bowel by travelling around the world eating strange and wonderful things .
From public railings at railway stations to flushing toilet buttons , the task definitely put his immune system to the test .
