Olympic Games : Flagrant Doping Test Fraud
The IOC wants to set up a disciplinary commission to deal with the case .
Kenya &apos;s track and field is at risk of disaster after the second doping affair at the Rio de Janeiro Olympics .
After an attempt at doping control in the Olympic village , Kenya has sent a trainer home .
The International Olympic Committee announced that it would immediately set up a disciplinary commission to investigate the case .
A Kenyan official had announced that John Anzrah , a former sprinter and present @-@ day coach , had given an urine test at the Olympic Village under the name of the 800 @-@ meter runner Ferguson Rotich .
This was reported to Kenyan team management by the doping inspectors .
The International Federation of the International Atomic Energy Agency ( IAAF ) has asked the IOC for information on the case in order to launch its own investigations , said an IAAF spokesman .
&quot; Depending on the results of the investigation and subsequent IOC actions , the IAAF will carry out an evaluation , &quot; said an IAAF statement .
&quot; He ( Anzrah ) went to the doping control station and passed himself off as Ferguson Rotich , handed in the rehearsal and signed it , &quot; declared Kenya &apos;s head of mission Stephan Arap Soi .
He was accredited by the athlete who was on the World Anti @-@ Doping Agency &apos;s training control list .
By 2015 , Ferguson Rotich had finished fourth in the Beijing World Cup over 800 meters .
Four days earlier , Kenya &apos;s athletics delegation leader , Michael Rotich , had been withdrawn from the Rio Games .
In return for payment , he is reported to have informed athletes in his country of upcoming doping tests .
According to media reports , he was arrested at Nairobi airport on his return .
Kenya has been under special scrutiny at the IOC for some time now , following numerous doping offences .
When the IOC announced more than 2,000 doping targets prior to the Rio Games , it was unusual to note in advance that Kenya and Russia would be targeted in particular .
Before the summer games in Brazil , the World Anti @-@ Doping Agency put a lot of pressure on the African country to create an anti @-@ doping law and a functioning control system .
The law was passed a few weeks before the start of the Olympic Games .
WADA subsequently removed Kenya from the list of countries whose fight against doping is in accordance with WADA rules .
Kenya is regarded as a great runner nation .
The country &apos;s track and field athletes won the most medals at the 2015 World Cup in Beijing .
In a number of ARD television reports , repeated accusations have been made that doping funds are easily accessible in Kenya and that there is to be a significant mentality in sports fraud .
IOC member Richard Pound recently called for a similar investigation in Kenya to the one he conducted in Russian athletics .
It has been proven that doping was widespread and systematic in this sport .
Russia &apos;s track and field athletes were subsequently banned from the summer games .
