Turkey : The Kurdish community expects mass migration
&quot; Those who do not adapt and praise Erdogan are sitting on packed suitcases , &quot; says Ercan Karakoyun , Chairman of the Gülen @-@ related Foundation Dialog und Welt .
The Kurdish community in Germany expects tens of thousands of asylum seekers to flee Turkey to Germany in the short term .
In the medium term , it could even be &quot; a few hundred thousand , &quot; according to the association &apos;s chairman , Ali Toprak .
As a result of Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan &apos;s crackdown following the attempted coup , the Kurdish community in Germany is expecting a mass flight to Germany .
&quot; In the short term , I expect tens of thousands of asylum seekers from Turkey to come to Germany , and in the medium term , a few hundred thousand from Turkey , if the Erdogan regime continues to fight minorities and the democratic opposition , &quot; said Ali Toprak , head of the association , of Friday &apos;s &quot; World . &quot;
Because the government covered Kurdish strongholds with punitive actions months ago , 500,000 Kurds have fled within Turkey .
After the failed coup , secular and opposition ethnic Turks would be added .
Many in Europe will want to start over if they continue to be oppressed in Turkey .
&quot; It cannot be that a state that takes in refugees itself produces refugees in its own country , &quot; Toprak said .
The association &apos;s leader lamented the targeted location of Syrian Arabs in Kurdish cities , but also in Alevian cities .
By doing so , Erdogan wanted to increase the pressure on the remaining Kurds to leave .
&quot; They are the last large minority in Turkey , the Christian Armenians and Greeks have already been exterminated or expelled in the last hundred years , &quot; said Toprak , who is also a member of the CDU .
The head of the association demanded that the federal government &quot; take as strong a stand as Austria against Erdogan and his supporters . &quot;
In Germany , too , there is a &quot; witch hunt &quot; against Erdogan critics .
For the first time in recent months , I no longer feel safe in Germany .
The German branch of the Gülen movement also fears the flight of many Turks abroad .
More Turks will seek asylum in Germany , especially Kurds and opposition figures .
Labelling as a Gülen follower destroys teachers and other academics &apos; professional existence .
&quot; Those who fail to adapt and praise Erdogan are sitting on packed suitcases , including Kemalists and seculars , &quot; said Ercan Karakoyun , Chairman of the Gülen @-@ related Dialogue and Education Foundation , the &quot; world . &quot;
According to figures from the Federal Ministry of the Interior , even before the coup , the Turks constituted the largest group of asylum seekers in Germany who were recognised for political persecution .
As of the cut @-@ off date of 30 June , this had been 11,386 people , which is just under 29 percent of all those recognised as eligible for asylum ( 39,625 ) .
This survey does not include those who have fled war , poverty or lack of prospects .
According to the Basic Law , the right to asylum is exclusively a matter of politics , that is , of the state , of individual persecution .
Mecklenburg @-@ Western Pomerania : &quot; Go where it hurts . &quot;
Bizarre Mecklenburg @-@ Western Pomerania : The locals are not aware of the summer election campaign - and the holiday makers from North Rhine @-@ Westphalia are not allowed to choose the state parliament .
In Mecklenburg @-@ Western Pomerania , they understood .
In 2021 , the regional elections will not take place directly at the end of the summer holidays , the Schwerin Parliament decided at the beginning of the year .
Because we cannot be more stupid than we have been up to now : summer holidays , heat and a national election campaign - that bites .
The locals , who are supposed to be convinced by the election campaigns , are on holiday .
Most of the holidaymakers who are in the country , travelling on Usedom , Rügen or Hiddensee , are not locals , so they are not allowed to choose the provincial parliament .
There are also practical problems : during the holidays , helpers who hang up posters , blow balloons , distribute flyers and ultimately count votes are difficult to find .
Until September 4 , 2016 , the election day and the last holiday day , Mecklenburg @-@ Western Pomerania must go through yet another election campaign close to the people .
The hot phase , if that can be said at all , has just begun .
And it is also about something : Prime Minister Erwin Sellering , leader of an SPD / CDU coalition , must fear for his position .
The SPD , the strongest party since 1998 , is now clearly behind the CDU in polls .
It will be exciting to see how much newcomer AfD scores and what remains of a coalition fit in the end .
Sellering , 66 years old and the head of government since 2008 , is conducting an almost unobtrusive election campaign , to say nothing of his big posters .
He travels around the country distributing roses and chatting a little with people , just as his legendary , meager predecessor Harald Ringstorff did .
Otherwise , Seelering has got cold feet and blames Chancellor Merkel for the blooming of the AfD .
Her refugee policy , her &quot; we can do it , &quot; has accelerated the rise of right @-@ wing populists , which will probably cost him his beautiful job now .
The CDU , with its leading candidate , Interior Minister Lorenz Caffier , has already experienced what it is like to campaign in the right place at the wrong time .
She has twice invited German Chancellor Angela Merkel to large rallies ; Merkel is in the north @-@ east .
But the target group was wrong , it was more North Rhine @-@ Westphalia , Berlin and Saxony there than Mecklenburg and Western Pomerania .
&quot; There was probably a majority from other federal states , &quot; Vincent Kokert , Secretary General of the CDU in Mecklenburg @-@ Western Pomerania , recently complained in the NDR .
But nor is it a pity to listen to Angela Merkel from other corners of Germany .
Otherwise , the Northeast CDU largely dispenses with the usual campaign stands in market places and in front of shopping centres with umbrellas and balloons .
This , Kokert says , only plays a &quot; minor role . &quot;
The Union , too , has realised that it is shattering the grassroots in the countryside , that it has to make a great effort to reconnect with the people .
You are like the Left , the SPD , the Greens : in the vast expanses of the country almost non @-@ existent .
The CDU campaigner Kokert &apos;s advice to his comrades @-@ in @-@ arms , however , is also self @-@ revealing : &quot; They must go where it hurts , where the people are : village festivals , golden weddings , every birthday party must be used . &quot;
Because the stakes are high , Sellering has now called on his SPD to campaign with a high degree of commitment .
In surveys the Social Democrats were last 22 percent behind partners CDU ( 25 ) and only just ahead of AfD ( 19 ) .
In the 2011 election , the SPD had clearly won by 35.6 percent , ahead of the CDU ( 22 ) .
The Greens , a small party with 7 % in the polls , are likely to make the leap into parliament .
They are turning a holiday emergency into a modern virtue and are largely transferring their campaign to the Internet .
The country &apos;s president Claudia Müller calls it &quot; online election campaign . &quot;
Otherwise , green campaigners will search for native voters among holidaymakers .
Silke Gajek , the top contender , is just curving through the lakes of Mecklenburg on a houseboat and thinks it &apos;s beautiful .
Your impression : &quot; Electoral holiday in Mecklenburg @-@ Western Pomerania is not a punishment . &quot;
B27 Restoration : Restaurants are blocked
There is nothing wrong with the speed with which the B 27 is being cleaned up .
The people responsible for the construction work , which starts at 5.30 a.m. and only ends around 8 p.m. , are to be commended everywhere .
&quot; They &apos;ve done everything pretty badly , &quot; says Elvira Tetzlaff of the jet petrol station .
This is a super team .
There is no delay either .
At the beginning of the week the construction site was able to be moved to the south as planned , by the end of October everything should be ready .
There is also praise for the willingness of those responsible for the construction work to make concessions , for example when it comes to the establishment of emergency access routes .
Since the construction site moved south on Monday and the barrier on the asphalt road in Ofterdingen has also been lifted and the connection to Rottenburg has been restored , the traffic situation within the village has relaxed .
Citizens can now drive on the B 27 on both sides again from Ofterdingen .
The dodging traffic through the village seems to be declining .
&quot; In some cases , there have been considerable complaints , &quot; says Florian King , Deputy Chief Executive Officer in charge of traffic management of the rehabilitation .
The residents of Bachsatzstraße , Steinlach Road , Hafnerstraße and Weiherrain had to contend with more traffic noise , because many sidewalks sought out and trusted their navigators rather than signage .
As a result , some lorries dispersed into residential areas .
Since the speed limits were not observed either , the municipality increasingly requested the measuring vehicle from Mössingen .
&quot; There have been significant overruns , &quot; says King , who has been enquiring about the situation on the ground .
Two to three a minute have already been flash .
The fastest was 77 km / h in the Speed 30 zone .
Since the construction site has moved on , it has become calmer .
For the business people on the B27 , it is only a small consolation that the road is now open again for customers from Rottenburg .
Business people do not like to look in the cards .
But the fact that the B @-@ 27 &quot; s reorganisation has caused them a drop in sales is something that everyone who is asked reveals .
However , some are more and some are less affected .
For those who have less to do with the &quot; end customer , &quot; i.e. who produce for other companies , the reorganisation has little impact on them .
Thomas Sulz also speaks of a &quot; at most slight decline &quot; in the Maier dealership , but also admits that , of course , &quot; the running clientele is missing . &quot;
The pubs along the road are the most affected .
J. Albert Göhner , owner of the Steakhouse , formerly Krone , is very clear .
That is already a threat to existence .
Not only him , but all the restaurants &quot; hit hard . &quot;
The customers from Hechingen , Balingen and Rottweil were missing .
We have to be happy about every euro of turnover .
He puts the loss of sales at &quot; well over 50 percent . &quot;
Road rehabilitation had &quot; set back its operation by two years . &quot;
He had to lay off half of his staff .
If I had a company with 4 000 employees and half of them had been laid off , politics would have reacted differently .
Instead , when asked by Mr Göhner whether there could be any financial compensation , the President of the government , Mr Schmidt , replied that the restaurant would otherwise benefit from the advantages of the situation on the B 27 . Now it would also have to bear the disadvantages arising from the renovation .
Göhner knows from other counties where such things have been handled more generously .
For all complaints , Göhner is sure that his restaurant will continue to exist .
After all , the family business has been here since 1715 , pointing to its long history .
He can understand why other regular visitors are now less likely to turn a blind eye because of complicated traffic management .
If you can &apos;t drive here , it &apos;s beautiful elsewhere .
Göhner has no doubt that his regular clients will come back when the renovations are finished .
Despite the BSE and avian flu crises , Göhner considers the impact of the B 27 construction works on his customers to be the biggest crisis his restaurant has experienced in its long history .
Six months of construction work is already brutal .
Laws are constantly being rolled back in the name of combating terrorism .
After the recent attacks , Interior Minister de Maizière is now presenting a thick security package .
But what does toleration status have to do with terror ?
And what does the coalition partner have to say about all this ?
Thomas de Maizière gives the reconciler .
All his proposals are &quot; politically acceptable &quot; to the coalition partner , says the Federal Minister of the Interior when he presents his new security package .
You are not asking too much of anyone .
Other , more far @-@ reaching issues would first be discussed within the parties .
I am participating in that as well .
As Minister of the Interior , however , he wants results and an &quot; attainable consensus &quot; within the coalition .
After the recent attacks in Würzburg and Ansbach , De Maizière took a little time before presenting his conclusions on security in the Republic .
But they are all the more extensive for that .
Some things are already known , announced and targeted : the fact that a new security authority is to deal with the cracking of encrypted communications is nothing new .
Nor does the fact that Germany has to implement several EU directives on passenger data and weapons law .
The call for more video surveillance and staff for the security authorities comes as no surprise either .
In part , de Maizière is launching a second attempt at proposals that could not previously be made with the SPD : he wants to criminalise the advertising of sympathy for terrorist groups and to strip jihadists with dual nationality of their German passport .
&quot; These are going to be difficult points for the SPD , &quot; the CDU man acknowledges .
Nevertheless , he believes that this is reasonable and is not demanding anything that does not stand a chance in the coalition partner anyway .
De Maizière also presents a few new ideas .
They are partly self @-@ contained : he is planning fast @-@ track procedures for deportations and more opportunities for detaining people before deportation .
Refugees who are specifically brought into the country should first have their smart phones checked and social media accounts revealed for security checks .
In condoning rejected asylum seekers , he wants to put some in an even worse position than before - for example , those who commit crimes or deliberately throw away their papers in order to hide their identity .
Some of this is politically and legally sensitive .
Some things also look half @-@ baked and leave questions unanswered .
And on a number of points - in the unequal treatment of those who have been sentenced , for example - the question arises : what does this actually have to do with security and terror ?
Yes , says de Maizière , it is important to distinguish between the issues of refugees and terror .
But it cannot be denied that the perpetrators of the Ansbach and Würzburg attacks were refugees .
Moreover , many people were concerned about security , given the high numbers of refugees .
And things that were deeply preoccupying people simply could not be ignored even in election campaigns .
There has been a huge focus on internal security .
First the attacks in the neighbourhood : Paris , Copenhagen , Brussels , Nice .
Then the attacks in Würzburg and Ansbach .
The uncertainty is great .
And yes , election campaigns are coming up .
The Union and the SPD are therefore placing themselves increasingly in a position where internal security is concerned .
In recent days , the two parties have been at each other &apos;s throats .
First a horrendous dispute about the equipment of the federal police , then about a collection of ideas on security policy from a number of Union interior ministers , in which the heads of the departments also demand a burqa ban and a renunciation of dual citizenship .
Here , too , De Maizière is striving for conciliatory tones .
He does not believe in abandoning the double pass .
We have calmed down the debate in Germany .
Reopening it would not make sense .
And he has constitutional concerns about a burka ban .
Whether his own package is constitutional at all points and whether it is actually &quot; reasonable &quot; for the coalition partner remains to be seen .
There is something in it that could cause a dispute .
But the SPD , too , is currently trying to make a name for itself when it comes to internal security .
Party leader Sigmar Gabriel is cautiously signaling his willingness to talk , saying , &quot; The SPD is prepared to talk about anything that will help to further increase security . &quot;
Volkswagen still manages to get away with it .
Despite diesel scandals , deliveries are rising worldwide .
But not all markets run smoothly .
In the recall campaign , there is a whistle about a term .
Volkswagen is starting the second half of the year more slowly with deliveries .
In spite of the diesel affair , Europe &apos;s largest car manufacturer can still show an increase this year thanks to its many brands and some well @-@ functioning markets .
In July , however , the core VW brand weakened mainly in Western Europe , putting a strain on overall sales once again , according to the listed company .
Worldwide , the VW brand sold 1.8 percent fewer vehicles in July with 449100 cars than in the previous month .
In Western Europe alone , which is the second most important market after China , sales were 14 percent down on the previous month .
Deliveries slumped by nearly one @-@ sixth in Germany &apos;s domestic market .
Jürgen Stackmann , Head of Brand Sales , attributed the weaker figures from July mainly to two sales days less in Europe .
Moreover , some core markets had been held back by &quot; changing economic conditions . &quot;
In addition to the situation surrounding the coup attempt in Turkey , the British vote to leave the EU also weighed on , explained one spokeswoman .
In the US , where the exhaust @-@ gas affair first escalated , there is also a minus .
The Chinese market is a major support to VW .
All in all , the mainly affected Lower Saxony household name is still getting off to a flying start as a result of the diesel scandal : after the first seven months , only 0.9 % of deliveries were cut to 3.37 million vehicles .
Group Sales Director Fred Kappler continued to show a sales bonus from January to July .
Volkswagen delivered 1.3 percent more vehicles during this period , and 5.904 million vehicles worldwide .
Volkswagen had manipulated exhaust gas tests with a software .
In Germany alone , VW is calling for around 2.5 million cars to be converted to the workshops .
In the course of the conversion , VW confirmed that the conversion of the cars would not have any negative effects .
There would be no deterioration in fuel consumption , CO2 emissions or engine power after the conversion of the vehicles .
After the conversion , the manufacturer issues customers with a &apos; guarantee certificate &apos; , but does not refer to it as a &apos; guarantee &apos; , as it was said in company circles on Friday .
This is because of legal niceties .
&quot; Focus &quot; had reported that Volkswagen is now after all granting its German customers a guarantee for converted diesel models .
This would have been confirmed last Monday by VW representatives in the Federal Ministry of Transport .
It was confirmed from the Ministry of Transport that this meeting took place .
&quot; VW has to comply fully with the requirements of my commission of inquiry and the KBA . &quot;
&quot; Deviations from this will not be accepted , &quot; declared Federal Minister of Transport Alexander Dobrindt ( CSU ) according to the Ministry .
VW has given a guarantee that fuel consumption , CO2 emissions or engine performance will not deteriorate after the conversion and that all type @-@ approval relevant vehicle values will remain unchanged .
Volkswagen itself , however , does not use the term &quot; guarantee , &quot; as it used to say in corporate circles .
Volkswagen sees the broad term &quot; guarantee &quot; as an opportunity for customers , for example , to come to a workshop six months after the conversion with engine damage - and to ascribe this to the new software , even if the damage has nothing to do with it .
It is also in the interests of the customer to prevent any other damage , which has nothing whatsoever to do with the exhaust scandal , from leading to uncertainty , as has been said , about possible guarantee regulations .
That is why VW does not use the term &quot; guarantee . &quot;
In the future , Raiffeisenbank Gmund am Tegernsee will demand punitive interest from wealthy savers - as the second institution in Germany .
On Thursday , bank manager Josef Paul said : &quot; We are talking about only 139 customers who park 40 million euros in current or current money accounts . &quot;
The Federal Association of German Banks speaks of an isolated case and does not see this as a signal : ordinary savers would &quot; not have to fear paying penalty for their savings interest . &quot;
If banks hold money overnight at the European Central Bank ( ECB ) , they must pay it 0.4 % penalty interest .
Starting in September , Raiffeisenbank Gmund will charge private and corporate customers back this fee for deposits over 100,000 euros in current or current money accounts .
&quot; The first EUR 100 000 is available . &quot;
&quot; The next 100,000 will cost 400 euros a year in the future , &quot; said Paul .
For some time now , he has been guarding EUR 40 million , which could be taken from one day to the next and which he cannot use .
&quot; They are in my central bank account and cost 0.4 per cent , &quot; said the bank chief .
&quot; I cannot lay down EUR 4 000 for every million . &quot;
He is now passing on the costs according to the &quot; polluter pays &quot; principle .
Simply leaving the cash in the safes of the Raiffeisenbank would be far too dangerous : &quot; I &apos;ve seen four raids before , I don &apos;t want the fifth one ! , &quot; said the bank &apos;s board .
Most clients would understand and switch to other forms of investment .
Few moved to other banks .
The Bavarian Cooperative Society declared : &quot; The extreme monetary policy stance of the ECB incurs considerable costs for all banks . &quot;
Carrying them alone is &quot; not economically possible in the long term . &quot;
Some German banks have therefore increased their fees for account management , credit cards or transfers .
In 2014 , Thuringian Volks- und Raiffeisenbank Altenburger Land , with its Skatbank branch , made the headlines with punitive interest on deposits of € 3 million or more .
Michael Kemmer , Chief Executive Officer of the Banking Association , said : &quot; We do not expect private customers to have to pay across @-@ the @-@ board fees for deposits ; competition among banks and savings banks in Germany is far too strong for that . &quot;
As one banker said , there is &quot; a clientele on Lake Tegernsee a little more richly endowed by wealth . &quot;
&quot; This can become a problem for a small bank &quot; if it guards money free of charge .
The cooperative bank Gmund , founded in 1911 , has branches in Bad Wiessee , Rottach @-@ Egern , Kreuth and Tegernsee .
Famous actors , athletes and entrepreneurs live in the region .
The Bavarian Cooperative Association &quot; currently does not know of any other banks that charge an excess for retail deposits , &quot; said Ernst .
The president of the German Association of Popular Banks and Raiffeisen Banks ( BVR ) , Uwe Fröhlich , declared at the end of June : &quot; The threshold for negative behaviour towards the private customer is very , very high . &quot;
Competition is fierce , and there is a threat that investors will migrate to compete .
Customers in Germany will not put up with this to a large extent .
Destination records : who is actually buying records ?
Lonely middle @-@ aged men love records .
Before you rush to the commentary section to inject harsh insults into it under the pseudonym Non @-@ Alledonym of Lonely Men &apos;s Medieval Age , this statement is derived from current data .
According to YouGov , the much @-@ talked @-@ about revival of records is due not to a boom in millennials who want to welcome the novelty of physical objects , but to midlife nostalgia .
Those who have recently bought a plate are most likely aged between 45 and 54 .
Indeed , the 18 @-@ 24 age group is the least likely buyer .
It is also not a hoard of amateur collectors - it has an emotional meaning : older record buyers keep their feelings for themselves ( 56 % vs. 53 % ) and enjoy spending time alone ( 69 % vs. 66 % ) .
But are the results of YouGov right ?
If this blog were a television news story , the camera would follow me as I walk in the middle of a busy street in Soho , wearing a modest grey suit and stuffing wild before I stop , holding my hands and saying something defining : &quot; So , let &apos;s take a closer look at it . &quot;
So let us take a look at it .
Even if the heart of Sohos is slowly losing its charm - hotels , restaurants , and offices are now filling the buildings that once housed independent sellers - there is still a handful of fantastic record stores .
I would probably ask the cameraman to turn off the camera for the next part , where I am in close proximity to various men in such shops and try to assess their age and mood by observing them .
Stuart from Glasgow , 55 , whom I follow from Sister Ray ( data number : two young women , three middle @-@ aged men ) to Reckless Records ( data number : eight middle @-@ aged men , one woman , presumably around the age of 20 ) , is a day in London for a meeting and goes through the shops to fill the few hours .
Is he a collector , I ask ?
&quot; I appreciate it , &quot; he says .
I have about 3,000 or 4,000 plates .
These records , pictured above ( he sent me the snapshot by e @-@ mail , I didn &apos;t follow him home ) , cover the walls of his living room .
The reason he owns such a considerable number of albums and singles is the result of his available income : he is now able to buy records that he could not afford when they appeared and buy again items that he sold when he was young and broke .
&quot; Many of the things I buy are from the late 60s , early 70s , when I was 11 or 12 , things that I was probably a little too young to buy , &quot; he says .
He agrees that those who buy records are more introverted and like to spend time alone , and adds : &quot; I don &apos;t smoke and I don &apos;t drink very much .
That is my vice .
Wez , 25 , who works at Sister Ray , also believes that many of the customers he meets apply to the YouGov profile .
However , he also noticed a new wave of people influenced by the media hog , people who heard about the comeback and felt prompted to buy their old records again .
From the conversations I have had , people usually got rid of their collection around 1998 or 1999 .
Customers who once sold their records to buy CDs are now selling their CDs to buy their records again , &quot; he says .
That would explain the boom in fans of record revival of a certain age .
But what about the supposed emotional meaning of records ?
It only takes a few seconds in a store like Phonica to realize that record stores offer a reassuring community of like @-@ minded people .
According to Wez , some of the older customers took offence at the contactless payment system .
Some record fans feel overwhelmed by the digital world and want to retreat to stability from familiar record covers , from objects that evoke happy youth memories .
&quot; I think sometimes it can be the filling of a void or the possession of material possessions as a kind of comfort , &quot; says Wez .
That is the case with me as a collector and I think it is the case with a lot of people .
It is an easy way to get mentally involved .
&quot; We are like their social workers ! &quot; one member of staff flutes from a pile of plates .
A survey by the ICM in April revealed that almost 50 % of the people who bought a record last month have not yet listened to it .
The survey also found that 41 % have a record player they never use , while 7 % of those who buy a record do not own a record player .
At this point in the news story , I would probably look very worried as I scroll through a stack of Bossa Nova compilations .
Jonny , 42 , who works on Sounds of the Universe ( data count : three middle @-@ aged men ) , noticed a &quot; trophy aspect &quot; of the revival .
&quot; Someone came in very recently and said , &quot; I don &apos;t own a record player , but I would like to buy a Radiohead record so I can put it on the shelf , &quot; he says .
This is not a large percentage , but it is definitely happening .
More product @-@ heavy , less music @-@ class .
We have people who say , &quot; I don &apos;t have a record player . &quot;
These are younger people , not older people , who are only slowly coming in .
Fopp , which has devoted almost an entire floor to the records , has a more colourful audience than I enter .
There are couples around 70 , tourists taking photos , teenage boys and middle @-@ aged women .
Even if the atmosphere is a little less relaxed than in the above shops - wild beasts of the latest synthesizer and sexpacked pop roar out of the speakers instead of experimental jazz - it is good to see such diversity among customers .
None of them looks very lonely , but gnawing mental traumas are hard to detect when standing next to someone for 30 seconds .
Elanora , 27 , has been running around in the shop for a few minutes looking at the variety of plates for sale .
It is more like a shop window shop than a large @-@ scale purchase .
It does not earn much , so collecting plates is not a real option , she says .
It costs a lot .
It &apos;s easy to listen to music from a computer or in other ways , but the beauty of records is ... &quot; she drives with a loving sigh .
I don &apos;t know how to explain it - it &apos;s really unique .
My last stop is a store that is said to have inspired a new generation of record lovers : Urban Outfitters .
While I seem to be patching the jeans hotpants , I see a group of young teenage girls clustering around Polaroid cameras for a moment before a father and his daughter consider buying a Crosley record player .
To the left is a staircase , a wall full of records of Adele , Jeff Buckley , Amy Winehouse and Fleetwood Mac : a mixture of contemporary music and classics that are essential for an average collection .
No one looks at them - perhaps because they are merely decorative , some so high up that it is impossible to touch them .
It is pure &quot; record art . &quot;
But , given that any attraction for these items could mean more money for the industry and send some customers to the depths of Sohos for more , there is nothing to complain about .
It is no surprise that a population that has more time and money than others is also the one that spends the most on luxury items like plates .
