A ray of hope for the German steel industry
The crisis @-@ hit and energy @-@ intensive German steel industry is spared millions in additional costs .
Financial burdens that threatened the industry from green electricity production are off the table .
The exemption from the renewable energy levy remains for existing installations for so @-@ called in @-@ house electricity production in the German steel industry , said Federal Minister of Economic Affairs Sigmar Gabriel ( SPD ) of the &quot; Westdeutsche Allgemeine Zeitung &quot; ( WAZ , Friday edition ) .
&apos;I am really pleased that we have finally been able to achieve this after two years of tough negotiations . &apos;
The European Commission therefore initially planned to make steel producers who use gases from the blast furnace to generate electricity for their own consumption pay .
According to the German Industry Association , the steel industry was threatened with additional costs of EUR 120 to 240 million per year .
Gabriel told WAZ that there is now an agreement in principle with the EU Commission following talks with Competition Commissioner Margrethe Vestager .
Only when the generators in the steel works are replaced will an EEG levy of 20 per cent be incurred .
But even this is not collected in the steel industry .
The IG Metall welcomed Germany &apos;s agreement with the EU Commission on Self @-@ Power Generation .
This would to a large extent enshrine the status quo of the previous system .
Gabriel &apos;s successful efforts are of particular importance to the steel industry .
&apos;This is a first step in relation to our &apos; steel is the future &apos; campaign .
&quot; More must follow . &quot;
&quot; Climate and employment objectives must also be weighed up when it comes to reforming emissions trading , &quot; IG Metall CEO Jörg Hofmann declared in Frankfurt .
The steel industry in Europe has suffered from overcapacity and considerable price pressure since the 2008 financial crisis .
The situation was further aggravated last year when the world &apos;s largest producer country , China , threw massive amounts of steel onto the world market in the face of weakening domestic demand .
European manufacturers accuse Chinese steel companies of price dumping .
Over the course of this spring , the situation has calmed down somewhat .
On the one hand , import duties imposed on imported steel are having an effect and , on the other , the economic prospects in China have brightened .
It is unclear how sustainable the price recovery is .
Thyssen was the German industry leader on Thursday and remained cautious .
Most recently , prices would have stagnated again .
The industry is responding to the difficult situation with further cost reductions .
Thyssen krupp did not want to rule out the closure of individual plants either .
At the end of 2015 , the German steel industry employed around 86,000 people .
In July , German steel manufacturers remain cautious despite rising prices and increasing orders .
At 3.4 million tonnes , they produced just over six percent less crude steel than in the previous month , according to the German Association of Steel and Steel on Friday .
After a short increase in May , the amount produced fell for the second month running .
Since the beginning of the year , production has been two percent lower than a year earlier .
Thanks to an improved order situation , the Association expects to see an increase in output in the coming months .
Community , Spirit , Health : Singing does Seniors Good
Singing has accompanied Ursel Kipp throughout her life : as a young girl she was in school choir , as a teacher she studied music , and today she sings in a senior choir .
&quot; Sing moves me - emotional and physical , &quot; she describes .
After a rehearsal , she says , she feels balanced , happy and , overall , more alive .
By the way , she is doing her health and mind good .
After all , singing is a great hobby for seniors from several perspectives , says Erhard Hackler of the German Senior Citizens League .
Most senior citizens sing in the choir and share the joy of music with like @-@ minded people , describes Hackler .
By being together regularly , senior citizens can make and maintain social contacts .
Because social and family structures often disintegrate in old age and a choir is then an ideal opportunity to spend time with other people .
Ursel Kipp also had this experience in her choir : &quot; To consult and organize , to be able to rely on each other and to learn from each other - a choir is a very special form of association . &quot;
Singing can be exhausting in a positive sense , Hackler says .
Seniors practice a deep and controlled breathing .
Those who regularly challenge their lungs do not get out of the doldrums so quickly , even in everyday life .
Even when it comes to maintaining the sound of voice in old age , singing is an optimal hobby .
According to Ursula Lenz of the German Association of Senior Citizens &quot; Organizations , singing often has a very special effect on older people .
In the older generations , singing together was much more important ; it was part of everyday life , both at school and at leisure , she explains .
Lenz often observes that singing or listening to songs awakens many memories in older people , often associated with positive feelings of their youth .
Song lyrics , and especially melodies , remind people with dementia of events long ago .
When singing , Lenz explains , the head is also required to perform particularly well .
Focusing simultaneously on one &apos;s own voice and on a given rhythm , while adapting to the other singer , is a major cognitive challenge .
Older people in particular , who live alone , practice so that they do not just focus on themselves .
Another positive aspect is the recognition you get from singing in the choir , Hackler says .
An enthusiastic audience is a great praise .
The sense of self @-@ worth also grows through singing in a choir .
To show oneself : If I practice for a long time for something , I get better and grow beyond myself - to strengthen this experience .
So there are plenty of good reasons to start singing .
If you want to try a new hobby , don &apos;t hesitate - even if you think you have little talent , Lenz advises .
You don &apos;t sing alone - with 50 singing people , who can hear when a sound goes by ?
According to Hackler , senior citizens have various options when looking for a suitable offer .
If someone from your circle of friends sings in a chorus of old people , you can simply join in .
Many cities also offer overviews of the choirs in the area .
If you want to sing in a church choir , you can contact the congregation or the head of the church directly .
Many senior choirs can also be found on the Internet .
Those who do not have access to the Internet can ask their family , friends or neighbours for help in searching the Internet .
Hackler advises those who are interested in singing to definitely join a choir .
Singing is good for the soul and has something liberating - this applies to all ages .
Cats are more sensitive than cats to the cries of the young .
Biologists in Hanover have studied the effect of calling cat babies on adult animals .
To their surprise , the mice did not leave the males cold either - however , they always behaved the same as the females .
Female cats can recognize the irritation level of cat babies by the miking of the little ones .
They react ten per cent faster to sounds from kittens who think they are in great need , as scientists from the Veterinary College and the Medical College Hannover ( MHH ) have found out .
Dogs also react to the calls of kittens - but always the same .
MHH biologist Wiebke Konerding said : &quot; Obviously , the acoustic differences between masculine masculine masculine masculine masculine masculine masculine masculine masculinity are either invisible or insignificant .
She is the first author of the study published this Friday in the trade journal &quot; BMC Evolutionary Biology . &quot;
In a previous study , the research team had already found that the duration and pitch of the kitten cries vary with the urgency of their need for help .
A total of nine adult males and eight females from the MHH breeding were observed .
On the one hand , they were played off with cries from little ones who were taken out of the throw box for three minutes and separated from their mother and siblings .
On the other hand , they were confronted with calls from more excited kittens , which were raised in addition .
Researchers believe that their findings are meaningful , despite the small sample .
&quot; All females , even those who didn &apos;t have their own offspring , reacted differently to the screams , &quot; Konerding said .
They turned more quickly to the loudspeaker when it was playing the calls of the more animated kittens .
This ability may be congenital or develop with sexual maturity .
&quot; One surprise was that the males responded at all , &quot; said the biologist .
Scientists have , on several occasions in the past , examined men &apos;s and women &apos;s reactions to baby sounds .
Again , some studies showed that women were more sensitive to infants , whether they were already mothers or not , biologist Marina Scheumann reported .
