The 34 @-@ year @-@ old Justin Gatlin has already been banned twice for drug use ( 2001 and 2006 ) .
Rio de Janeiro - Whistle blogger Julia Stepanova is not allowed to start in Rio .
Other convicted track and field sinners can only laugh at it - they are fighting for medals in Rio .
The issue of doping continues to dominate the headlines at the Rio Olympics .
Yuliya Yefimova , a Russian swimmer who had claimed her right to start just before the Games after a ban on doping , was ruthlessly beaten up and booed at her start ( 100 metres breast ) .
It was a bizarre scene : with a smile on her face , she had still stumbled into the hall and had provoked with her performance .
When it was clear that she was not going to get gold , the audience erupted into a cheering storm .
But there are many other athletes who , despite the doping past , will be taking part in the Olympic Games in Rio .
Here is an outline :
Justin Gatlin ( 100 , 200 , 4x100 m relay / USA ) : The 34 @-@ year @-@ old is one of the most controversial figures in athletics .
He has already been banned twice for drug use ( 2001 and 2006 to 2010 ) .
Since his spell , the 2004 Olympic champion and former World Champion have been running even faster than before , more than 100 m in 9.80 seconds making him the number one in the world and the biggest challenger to Usain Bolt .
Shelly @-@ Ann Fraser @-@ Pryce ( 100 , 4x100 m relay / Jamaica ) : In 2010 , the two @-@ time Olympic champion and seven @-@ time World Champion had to serve a six @-@ month suspension after she had been shown to have taken the pain @-@ killing Oxycodon .
She had severe toothache after an operation , the 29 @-@ year @-@ old defended herself .
Sandra Perkovic ( Diskus / Croatia ) : In 2011 , the Olympic champion from 2012 , World Champion from 2013 and European Champion from 2010 to 2016 were tested positively for the banned stimulant methylhexanamine .
Perkovic denied taking it knowingly and was suspended for six months .
The four biggest litters this year are the result of the big gold favorite .
LaShawn Merritt ( 200 , 400 , 4x400 m relay / USA ) : The Beijing Olympic champion and twice world champion over 400 m , had been tested positive in 2010 and was locked up for 21 months .
A penis enlargement remedy was responsible , Merritt claimed .
This year , the 30 @-@ year @-@ old over 200 and 400 m is the fastest man in the world .
Iwan Tichon ( Hammer litter , Belarus ) : Few athletes were subsequently deprived of so many medals .
For example , Tichon lost his 2005 World Championship title nine years later when he found testosterone doping .
The meanwhile 40 @-@ year @-@ old also had to hand over Olympic silver in 2004 because of steroid doping and the 2006 European Championship because of testosterone abuse .
He also won back the bronze medal of the 2008 Olympic Games following a ruling by the International Court of Sports ( CAS ) .
At 80.04 m it is in second place in the world ranking .
Liu Hong ( 20 km Walk , China ) : The world record holder and gold favorite was only tested positive in May , but is still allowed to start in Rio .
Evidence of the use of a banned food supplement was found in the 29 @-@ year @-@ old World Cup champion , while the ban on the World Anti @-@ Doping Agency WADA was mild and ended on 13 July .
Bomb terror in Thailand - Austrian injured - Several dead
The Austrian Embassy in Thailand is in contact with the woman , said the Foreign Ministry spokesman , Thomas Schnöll , on Friday morning .
She had suffered cuts and had been treated in hospital , but was already able to leave it .
She planned her return trip at the beginning of September .
Whether the other explosions on Phuket as well as in the southern cities of Surat Thani , Phang Nga , Trang and Chumphon also affect Austrian citizens is unclear for the time being .
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs is in constant contact with the local authorities in this regard , according to Schnöll .
In Hua Hin , approximately 200 kilometres south of Bangkok , two bombs first exploded on Thursday evening in an entertainment district .
According to the police , one Thai woman had been killed and about 20 people injured , including the Austrian woman , three Germans , three Dutch and three Italians .
On Friday morning , two more explosions went up again and , according to the authorities , another person was killed .
A bomb explosion was also reported from Phuket in the morning .
According to police , a taxi driver was injured during the detonation near the beach Patong , which is popular with tourists .
Another bomb then exploded in Surat Thani , on the south @-@ east coast of the country , killing an urban employee .
According to the authorities , the explosive device was blown up in a flower bed in front of the coastal police station .
Detonations in Phang Nga and Trang on the south @-@ west coast and in Chumphon on the south @-@ east coast caused a number of injuries .
The explosion in Hua Hin is believed to be linked to this .
&quot; The bomb attacks bear the same hallmark , &quot; army general Danai Kritmethavee told journalists on Friday morning .
&quot; We assume that it is a coordinated attack . &quot;
It is too early to comment on possible motives , but they are probably the actions of Muslim rebels .
Thai media , too , wanted the attacks to reflect a pattern typical of Muslim separatist bombings in the south of the country .
The Thai police , on the other hand , said that the attacks were not linked to the Islamist insurgency or to international terrorism .
&quot; This is only local sabotage , limited to limited areas and provinces , &quot; said one speaker in Bangkok .
Rather , it is believed that the bombs were planted by opponents of the ruling military junta .
The authorities would have received intelligence reports in recent days of imminent attacks in the south of the country - but they were not aware of the exact timing and locations .
It is not yet clear which group is behind the attacks .
The police instructed their officials throughout the country to strengthen security around key government buildings , as well as airports , train stations , tourist attractions , restaurants and entertainment districts .
There are always smaller bombings in Thailand , but they are mostly not directed against tourists .
Hua Hin is home to a palace that has been used for years by Thailand &apos;s King Bhumibol Adulyadej .
Following the recent bomb explosions , the Austrian Ministry of Foreign Affairs is recommending on its website that the Thai security authorities follow the instructions at all costs .
High security risk ( Level 3 ) applies to the provinces of Narathiwat , Yala , Pattani and Songhkla as well as Preah Vihear and the surrounding area .
After confrontations between the security forces and Muslim sections of the population , we advise against unnecessary trips to these provinces .
Increased security risk ( security level 2 ) applies to the rest of the country .
The attacks on Thursday and Friday came a few days after a controversial referendum on a constitution drafted by the military junta .
This gives the military great influence in the years to come as well .
Junta leader and prime minister Prayut Chan @-@ o @-@ cha said that the bombs were an attempt to create chaos as the country moves towards stability , an improvement in the economy and tourism .
The military junta that seized power in 2014 after a period of bloody unrest prides itself on having restored stability and order to the Kingdom .
But the military has also failed to stem the Muslim insurgency that has been smouldering for years in the far south of the country .
More than 6.500 people have already been killed in the conflict .
Less than a year ago , in Bangkok , an attack on a popular Hindu shrine also killed 20 people - most of them foreign tourists .
It was the most bloody attack in the country &apos;s recent history .
The right @-@ wing &quot; Identitarian Movement &quot; has been targeted by the Federal Office for Constitutional Protection .
After several state offices , the constitutional protectors in the federal government have also monitored the group .
&quot; We see in the &apos; Identitarian Movement &apos; evidence of efforts against the liberal democratic order , &quot; said Hans @-@ Georg Maaßen , head of constitutional protection of the German Press Agency in Berlin .
Immigrants of the Islamic faith or from the Middle East are being vilified in an extremist way .
That is why we are watching the movement now .
The &quot; Identitarian Movement &quot; is a group with French roots that has also been active in Germany since 2012 .
It is directed against &quot; multiculturalism , &quot; &quot; uncontrolled mass immigration , &quot; and the &quot; loss of one &apos;s identity through alienation . &quot;
Constitutional defenders in nine federal states - Bremen , Bavaria , Hesse , Berlin , Baden @-@ Württemberg , NRW , Lower Saxony , Saxony and Thuringia - are already observing the &quot; identitaries . &quot;
He said that his authority had consulted closely with the national authorities in taking the decision .
&quot; Groups like the &apos; Identitarian Movement &apos; are trying to get their target group where it is , &quot; said the head of constitutional protection .
In general , extremists try to address them with youth @-@ oriented language , often with poppy music .
Both Islamists and right @-@ wing extremists would do that .
This is not an attractive advertisement for one &apos;s own cause .
The propaganda is meant to appeal to people emotionally .
Young people are particularly vulnerable to this .
This is dangerous .
Most recently , there had been reports from several German states of &quot; identitarian &quot; contacts with AfD politicians .
He meticulously said that he had no knowledge of this .
Possible contacts of this kind would only be relevant to constitutional protection at a certain point .
What matters is whether the party in question - in this case , the AfD - changes direction and becomes extremist through certain individuals who are extremists .
So what matters is whether such individuals have a controlling influence on the party .
There is no sign of that .
In view of the marked increase in rights @-@ based crime and attacks on asylum seekers and refugee accommodation , he said moderately that he would not yet speak of new right @-@ wing terrorism in this context .
In recent years , however , we have discovered that there can be legal terrorism structures .
There was the Old School Society group or the Friday Group .
It may well be that other right @-@ wing terrorist groups or micro @-@ groups are forming , planning attacks against asylum seekers , against refugee homes or attacks for other extreme right @-@ wing motives .
However , there is no evidence of a German or European @-@ wide control of legal terrorism .
The previous groups were created at regional level or in social networks .
There was concern that many assaults were committed by people who had not previously appeared on the right @-@ wing scene .
That is the worrying thing .
Many of those suspected of committing attacks on asylum accommodation were not previously known as criminals , politically motivated criminals or right @-@ wing supporters .
&quot; In other words , many people committed crimes that were previously completely unrelated to right @-@ wing extremists , who were perhaps politically indifferent or , for example , voted in favour of the CDU , the SPD or the Left , but who then radicalised themselves through extreme right @-@ wing sentiment . &quot;
