From 1 October 2016 , the fee per cubic metre of waste water for the Neudorf / Reuth / Welschenkahl sewage plant will be 3.44 euros instead of 2.10 euros ; for Zultenberg / Lindenberg / Lopp 3.36 euros ( 2.26 euros so far ) and for Azendorf 3.64 euros ( 2.18 euros so far ) .
At the Azendorf plant , the cost of wastewater will be increased again at the latest if appropriate improvements are needed .
After a rough calculation , the waste water price in Azendorf will be EUR 4.37 per cubic metre .
As Mayor Bernd Steinhäuser ( CSU ) reported , when the County Council Office of Kulmbach approved the budget , it was found that there were subwellings for these sewerage plants .
The Kasendorf market was legally obliged to cover the costs of the investments .
From 1 October 2016 , citizens , as well as businesses and industries in Welschenkahl , Neudorf , Reuth , Azendorf , Lopp , Lindenberg and Zultenberg will have to dig deeper into their pockets .
The fee increases vary between 48 and 67 percent .
Management Director Herbert Schmidt pointed out to the Board that it was necessary to recalculate the fees for sewage treatment facilities in the market community .
In the period from October 2016 to September 2020 , overruns or undercuts from the previous calculation period should also be compensated .
Schmidt justified the serious increase in charges on the grounds that all three sewage plants were relatively small and had a very low volume of waste water , ranging from 6800 to 12000 cubic metres per year .
For example , due to the small distribution base , expenditure on necessary repairs amounting to several thousand euros would have a serious impact .
In addition , the volume of wastewater in all three plants has fallen slightly .
Furthermore , in the past calculation period , all three plants incurred a considerable amount of restoration and repair costs , not least because of their age .
The Azendorf plant is almost 30 years old , the Welschenkahl , Neudorf and Reuth plants as well as Zultenberg , Lindenberg and Lopp plants are almost 20 years old .
Schmidt pointed out that the mechanical ventilation system at the Azendorf sewage plant had to be replaced due to damage .
At the Welschenkahl pumping station , the almost 20 @-@ year @-@ old pumping equipment had to be completely overhauled , and at the Lopp water treatment plant , after almost 20 years of operation , the first sewage pond had to be dismantled , the sewage sludge disposed of and an additional ventilation facility installed in order to be able to continue to comply with water regulations .
Schmidt : &quot; In addition to these extraordinary expenses came the continued maintenance and maintenance costs , which must be taken into account accordingly in the new calculation period . &quot;
The same applies to electricity costs , which , according to the previous calculation in 2011 / 2012 , were still well below the current level .
Stone houses made it clear that the low volume of waste water in the three plants &quot; fully &quot; dissipated the costs of operation and maintenance .
Schmidt added that over the past 20 years the market community has not had to bear the heavy maintenance costs of sewage treatment .
In the opinion of stone houses , the situation for these installations will continue to be precarious in the long term , especially since it will not be possible to extend the supply area of the Friesenbachtal sewage treatment plant to include these plants because they are deficient facilities .
Bulgaria records inflation for the first time in 8 months
National statistics show that inflation in Bulgaria in July was 1 % on a monthly basis .
This is the highest level ( since June 2012 ) and the first above @-@ zero since October last year , when a positive 0.2 % was recorded .
Annual average inflation over the past 12 months ( August 2015 - July 2016 ) compared to the previous 12 months ( August 2014 - July 2015 ) was -0.8 % relative to the CPI .
The consumer price index in July 2016 was 101.0 % relative to June 2016 , or 1.0 % monthly inflation .
Inflation since the beginning of the year ( July 2016 , compared to December 2015 ) has been -0.2 % and annual inflation in July 2016 was -0.2 % compared to July 2015 .
In July 2016 , there was an increase in the prices of the following categories of consumer goods compared to the previous month : food and non @-@ alcoholic beverages ( 1.7 % ) ; transport ( 1.8 % ) ; leisure and culture ( 6.3 % ) ; restaurants and hotels ( 1.2 % ) ; various goods and services ( 0.3 % ) .
Prices fell for clothing and shoes ( 2.2 % ) ; furniture , household appliances and routine maintenance ( 0.5 % ) ; health ( 0.1 % ) .
Prices remained the same as in the previous month for alcoholic beverages and tobacco ; housing , water , electricity , gas and other fuels ; communications ; and education remained unchanged .
Criticized Snapchat &apos;s &quot; Anime &quot; Effect as an Asian Caricature
Snapchat says this filter is anime @-@ inspired , but some observers say it is insensitive to races .
With its filter tool Snapchat enables around 150 million daily users to change reality and play with identities in a way that verges on the absurd .
You can transform yourself into a pineapple , a dog or a figure that could be made of a Roy Lightstone painting .
The filters are blunt , property @-@ twisting tools that generate more than 30 million improved selfs a day .
All missteps are made public .
Snapchat filters have attracted criticism in the past , accusing them of promoting Blackface or promoting white skin as an ideal of beauty .
This week , when some users proposed a filter that gave them slit eyes , false teeth , and stained cheeks , some critics called it an Asian racist caricature - &quot; Yellow Face . &quot;
They wondered if these repeated controversies pointed to a bigger problem that the company has with diversity .
The news and indignation spread widely on Wednesday , with reports from The Verge and Motherboard , the day after Snapchat announced that it had disabled the feature .
The company offered an apology : the filter was intended as a tribute to anime characters , not a caricature of Asians .
But outsiders who have experienced racism were reminded by the filter of hurtful cliches .
Others firmly rejected the Anime settlement .
In an e @-@ mail , Grace Sparapani , a Korean @-@ American art student whose tweet was widely spread through the photographs , wrote that the filter was &quot; offensive and , to say the least , unpleasant . &quot;
She added that &quot; it is difficult to argue against a very loathsome Asian cartoon and filter effects .
It shows that the filter is not yellow @-@ eyed , but that the yellow face has been dragged to the depreciating extreme .
Snapchat is not the only company to cross this cultural tripwire .
American culture seems to be caught up in an endless struggle for diversity and integration , from conference rooms to Hollywood and the equipment we all hold in our hands .
And Snapchat &apos;s large audience of young people - who are more diverse about race than their older counterparts - may be more likely to expect sensitivity .
When one of Snapchats filters creates an image that is offensive to a user , &quot; it &apos;s much harder for such things to go unnoticed than they used to , &quot; said 25 @-@ year @-@ old Katie Zhu in a Thursday interview .
On Thursday , Zhu , who works as a product manager and medium engineer , decided to delete her Snapchat account and asked others to do the same .
In an essay for medium and a telephone interview , she said she believed that race @-@ related controversies reflected a lack of diversity in Snapchat recruitment practices .
Zhu criticized the largely white , male leadership and ended her essay with a hash tag : # DeleteSnapchat .
&quot; Either she does not have diverse representation of people with different skin colours in her staff so that they can make such choices , &quot; said the Sino @-@ American Mr. Zhu , &quot; or they have people with different skin colors who work there , but who are not in positions where they feel safe or comfortable , to say what against . &quot;
Others share her opinion , a complaint that Snapchat has largely left unanswered .
The company does not publish figures on the diversity of its workforce and points to its status as a private company .
On Thursday Snapchat refused to discuss the cultural backgrounds of its employees but , according to a spokesman , the company has recently recruited a human resources officer focused on under @-@ represented groups and on internal integration efforts .
Zhu , for her part , said that she would close her Snapchat account and added , &quot; I wonder if they need more users like us to be able to say that this is not OK . &quot;
Military leaders falsify ISIS intelligence , Congressional committee finds
Military personnel of the United States Central Command changed intelligence to paint a more optimistic picture of the war against the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than the actual conditions on the ground would have allowed , a congressional commission of inquiry reported in a report on Thursday .
The preliminary report , prepared by a task force of Republican members of the Armed Forces Committee , the Intelligence Committee , and the Military Budget Committee , reports great dissatisfaction among Central Command intelligence analysts , who reported how superiors changed their assessments of America &apos;s efforts to fight the Islamic State .
The Central Command , or Cencom , is the military headquarters in Tampa , Florida that controls American military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia .
&quot; Intelligence , typically nodded off by high @-@ level Centcom commanders , regularly painted a more positive picture of America &apos;s anti @-@ terrorism efforts than actual conditions on the ground allowed , and were consistently more positive than analyses by other intelligence agencies , &quot; one newspaper article quoted .
&quot; What happened at the Centcom is unacceptable - our soldiers suffer when bad analyses are presented to our political leaders , &quot; said Ken Calvert , a Republican member of the House of Representatives .
Mistakes in leadership in the Centcom reach to the top of the organization .
The ten @-@ page report details persistent problems in 2014 and 2015 in the descriptions and analyses of America &apos;s efforts to train Iraqi forces .
Although there is no direct evidence that Obama &apos;s leaders have given instructions to change the reports , it shows how analysts have been under pressure from their superiors to paint a more optimistic picture of the threat to the Islamic State , also known as ISIS or ISIL .
&quot; During the first half of 2015 , many Central Command press releases , statements and congressional statements were significantly more positive than they really were , &quot; the report noted .
For example , a Centcom official publicly announced that a military reconquest of Mossul could begin as early as April or May 2015 .
Mosul , Iraq &apos;s second largest city , remains under the control of the Islamic State .
&quot; So much is clear after months of investigation , &quot; Mike Pompeo , a Republican congressman from Kansas , said in a statement .
From mid @-@ 2014 to mid @-@ 2015 , the leaders of the Central Command changed the intelligence reports to minimize the danger posed by ISIS in Iraq .
The Republicans created the task force after they were told that analysts were worried about manipulation of reports on the Islamic State .
The report published on Thursday will be completed with more detailed findings as investigations continue .
In addition , further investigations of the Centcom reports are under way by the Inspector General of the Ministry of Defence .
Democratic members of the intelligence committee published their own findings on Thursday , which were in line with some of the Republican task force &apos;s conclusions .
&quot; In 2014 and 2015 , the Centcom created an overly restricted process for producing intelligence assessments of ISIL and the Iraqi security services , &quot; the senior Democrat on the committee , member of the House of Representatives Adam B. Schiff , announced in a statement .
This process , Mr. Schiff said , &quot; delayed the publication of intelligence reports , &quot; damaged the morale among analysts , and &quot; left too little room for dissent . &quot;
But Mr. Schiff and the Democrats said that they found no evidence of White House interference with the Centcom analysts regarding a &quot; certain political opinion . &quot;
The preliminary results of the Congress investigations were published on Tuesday by The Daily Beast .
Last August , The New York Times reported an investigation by the Pentagon &apos;s Inspector @-@ General , following complaints by Centcom analysts .
Lt. Cmdr. Patrick Evans , a Pentagon press officer , stated in a statement that the Department of Defense would not comment on congressional reports while the Inspector @-@ General &apos;s investigation was still ongoing .
But he also said that &quot; experts sometimes have divergent views on the interpretation of complex data , and intelligence services and the Ministry of Defense welcome a controversial discussion of these important issues of national defense . &quot;
The investigation has repercussions beyond the question of a successful American @-@ led air campaign in Iraq and Syria ( a claim now made by a growing number of Defense Department officials ) .
Last year &apos;s accusations , however , have raised the question of to what extent President Obama can rely on the Central Command to carry out honest assessments of the military operations in Iraq , Afghanistan , Libya and other crisis regions .
Criticism of secret information about the Islamic State is reminiscent of squabbles more than a decade ago , when a centcom analyst , Gregory Hooker , wrote a paper on how the then George W. Bush administration envisaged only a small occupying force in Iraq , contrary to the recommendations of many analysts , and spent little time worrying about the consequences of the 2003 invasion .
Mr. Hooker also played a key role in the insurrection against current coverage of the Islamic State .
Last year , Mr Hooker &apos;s team , according to government officials , found that , contrary to what the government had said , air strikes on refineries owned by the Islamic State had no significant impact on the terrorist group &apos;s finances , as they had started temporary refineries to sell oil on the black market .
This finding , however , was not made public , The Times reported in September .
Centcom &apos;s then commander , Gen. Lloyd J. Austin III , was criticized by members of the legislature for his overly positive assessment of the war situation in a Senate hearing .
General Austin retired in April and was replaced by Gen. Joseph L. Votel at the Central Command .
The US wins the fourth women &apos;s field hockey match , and a showdown with Britain looms .
One day after winning three goals in a 6 @-@ 1 victory over Japan , Katie Bam also scored the first two goals for the American women &apos;s field hockey team in a Thursday match against India that the American women won by 3 @-@ 0 .
Five goals in two matches should be a memorable achievement , but Bam ( 27 ) said she could not remember ever having done so .
&quot; I have no idea , &quot; she said .
I am not one of those people who remember their gates .
But she knows this : American women are 4 @-@ 0 in the Olympic race , and they are on par with British women , who remain unbeaten after winning 2 @-@ 0 against Japan .
Britain and the United States will meet on Saturday in the last match of the first round .
Both teams have already qualified for the quarter finals , and the game will decide which of them will take first and second place in their group of six teams .
The first place will evade the strong Dutch women who lead the other group for a little longer .
Whatever the outcome of Saturday &apos;s match , the American women &apos;s success story has unleashed a surprising commotion , four years after they finished last in 12 places at the last London Games .
Bam was part of that team .
She grew up in Blue Bell , Pennsylvania , and had a hockey stick in her hands for the first time at the age of three ( her two older sisters played the sport at Drexel University ) , and at the age of 16 she became the youngest national player in the history of the team .
She missed the 2008 Olympics because she couldn &apos;t qualify for the team .
Then came 2012 , when everything went wrong for her and her team .
The following year , Craig Parnham , an Englishman , became the coach of the national team , and things began to change for the better .
&quot; A change of culture , a mental change and a physical change , &quot; Bam said .
We did not have the amount of work in London that we now have .
We have been able to change course completely .
On Thursday evening , Bam opened the goalpost in the first half of the match with a knockback from the close range .
India entered the game without winning the tournament , but the team proved surprisingly tough , holding the score from 1 @-@ 0 to the third quarter until Bam took the game into her hands .
She did a sprint with the flat ball over the left flank , then pulled into the middle and dropped the ball into the goal to give the American women a 2 @-@ 0 lead .
Melissa Gonzalez made the final goal in the middle of the last quarter .
The shutout was the first in the entire tournament for the US goalkeeper , Jackie Briggs , who had to score one goal in each of the previous games .
It has a run .
Just like Bam .
&quot; We are in a good position , &quot; said Parnham , but how well will depend on the outcome of the next match on Saturday .
In the midst of the Rage of the Olympics , the Zen of the Trampoline
Wherever you are , however late it is , it is the Olympic Games .
The events in Rio de Janeiro feel constant and inevitable , a frantic relay race between competition and aspiration .
It is as if the Olympic torch itself were a burning rod stretching from the crossbow shooter to the swimmer to the triathlete .
You cannot turn on the TV , read a newspaper or listen in the coffeeshop queue to your neighbour &apos;s conversation without hearing about Simone Biles , Katie Ledecky or the dispute between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos .
And then there is Logan Dooley .
Dooley , who is attending the Olympic Games for the first time and is a flock of women with incantations , could very well have been under these well @-@ known names broadcast during prime time , built by sponsors and feel @-@ good TV ads , if he had been a swimmer , gymnast or even a fencer .
But Dooley , 28 , from Lake Forest , California , is fighting for gold in the Olympic trampoline tournament .
The Olympic flame does not shed equal light on every event .
Further from the centre , partly in the shade , there are sports that are not generally recognised : air pistol shooting , archery , badminton , taekwondo .
We will always have the chest swimming and may it last for a long time .
But if I could modestly make the case for my particular favorite , let me draw attention to the discreet charm of the trampoline .
Although trampoline jumping has been an Olympic event since 2000 , when it made its debut in Sydney , the last 16 years have been so sparsely perceived that many of those whom I had questioned did not know it was an Olympic sport at all .
This could also be regional ignorance .
Although the US sent athletes to compete , it has never won a trampoline medal , and by 2012 it had an athlete who made it to the final .
The Chinese and the Russians tend to share the prices for the men and the Chinese and the Canadians for the women .
Dong Dong from China and Rosie MacLennan from Canada will be defending their gold medals from London this year .
Trampoline jumping has a certain outsider charm , partly because it sounds more appropriate to the unenlightened ear for a clown school than to the Olympic Games .
At this point , I should admit that I am not an expert , just an earthly enthusiast .
It has humorous potential - the cartoon trembling of its never @-@ ending impact - but also the grace of exercising and diving , the two sports that essentially unite it .
The word &quot; trampoline &quot; comes from the Spanish El Trampoline , which means &quot; stepping stone . &quot;
Rising winners jump on a gigantic trampoline , shoot up to 30 feet in the air , and have to make a series of falling movements ( turning , picking , and saltos ) before they land on their feet .
According to the official Olympic program , they are rated according to execution , difficulty and &quot; flying time . &quot;
Twenty @-@ two athletes from 17 countries , 16 men and 16 women , will compete in Rio .
The most common Olympic vector is straight forward .
Medal @-@ hopeful must continue in their quest for gold , faster , up and over , sometimes to the finish , sometimes back and forth , up and down on the playground .
Not only do they hunt the finish line or the starting wall , but they also pursue another mocking target in television broadcasts : that of the world or the Olympic record .
The purposeful pursuit is noble , admirable , even fanatical - and it is enough to stir even a spectator &apos;s tears .
But it is also something that I myself find a bit tiring watching these games .
The trampoline offers a breathing space from this .
The vector of the trampoline jumper is above .
A move forward is not the aim .
He or she collides , seemingly weightless , like an astronaut , goes up , then down , then effortlessly up again .
Here , too , there is competition , not without difficulty , of course , but during the exercise there is no hectic attack on the goal , no vault far away , just the dreamlike , elegant suspension of time and gravity .
It &apos;s as Zen as the competition at the Olympics can only be .
Women &apos;s qualifying and final rounds will take place on Friday afternoon , in streaming at 1.00 Eastern Time ; men &apos;s matches at 1.00 p.m. on Saturday .
NBC will broadcast the final rounds as part of an afternoon block on both days starting at 2 p.m.
Amid Olympia mania , they promise a quiet , nice moment , one that is likely to be overlooked in the general turmoil .
If raising awareness can only be achieved through the fear and objectification of male athletes - as the male US gymnasts recently suggested , according to The Wall Street Journal - then Mr Dooley expects his new fan community , which is gasping for breath .
&quot; A generation of protests &quot; in Ethiopia , Long a US ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators calling for political change in Ethiopia were met with violent resistance from the government .
Witnesses testify that dozens of protesters were killed during clashes with the police during gun exchanges .
Is Ethiopia about to collapse ?
Over the past decade , it has been one of Africa &apos;s most stable countries , a solid Western ally with a fast @-@ growing economy .
But in recent months , protests against the government have shaken the country and spread to more and more areas .
Last week , thousands of people took to the streets demanding fundamental political changes .
The government &apos;s response , according to human rights organisations , has been ruthless .
Witnesses testified that police shot and killed dozens of unarmed demonstrators .
Videos circulating about the protests , which are probably from last year or the beginning of this year , show security men beating young people with sticks while forcing them to stand up against a wall .
The head of the UN Human Rights Agency is now calling for a thorough investigation .
&quot; It has always been difficult to keep this country together and in the future it will be even more difficult , &quot; said Rashid Abdi , project leader of the Horn of Africa of the International Crisis Group , a research group .
Ethiopia is the most populous country in Africa , after Nigeria , and its stability is valued by the West .
American military and intelligence agencies are working closely with Ethiopians to address the threat of terrorism beyond the region , particularly in Somalia ; few countries in Africa , if any , receive so much Western aid .
Ethiopia &apos;s economy expanded at a remarkable pace .
Its infrastructure has improved dramatically - there is a new commuter train in the capital , Addis Ababa .
The roads are generally quiet , safe and clean .
Even though Ethiopia has been anything but a model of democracy - human rights organisations have constantly led the way in government repression - the opposition in the country has been restricted , and dissidents have been effectively silence .
Many have been sent into exile or prison , killed or driven into the expanses of the desert .
But that could change .
&quot; If you oppress people and they have no other options but to protest , it erupts , &quot; said Seyoum Teshome , a lecturer in Central Ethiopia .
The whole of young people are protesting .
A generation protests .
There are numerous complaints that cover everything from land use to the stranglehold on the ruling coalition &apos;s power .
After a widely criticized election last year , the ruling party and its allies were given the opposition &apos;s last seat and now control 100 % of parliament .
At the same time , tensions are rising along the border with Eritrea ; a fight over this fragile , disputed line claimed hundreds of lives in June .
Analysts fear that separatists like the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front , which have been more or less vanquished in recent years , may take advantage of the turbulence and rearm themselves .
Several factors explain why feelings of bitterness are now exploding , after years of lying beneath the surface .
The first seems innocuous : smart phones .
Only in recent years have very many Ethiopians been able to communicate via social media , as cheaper smartphones became more common and Internet services improved .
Even if the government blocks access to Facebook and Twitter , as it does periodically , especially during protests , many people can still communicate via Internet proxies that hide where they are .
Several young Ethiopians said that they were gathering in protest in this way .
The second factor is that there is more solidarity between the Oromos and Amharas , the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia .
The Oromos and Amharas are not natural enemies .
Since then , the Amharas , who come from the predominantly Christian highlands , have prospered in politics and economics , while exploiting the Oromos , many of whom are Muslims and live in lowland areas .
But that , too , is changing .
&quot; We are coordinating under one umbrella , &quot; said Mulatu Gemechu , a leader of the Oromos .
The biggest protests took place in areas of the Amhara and Oromos .
Many Amharas and Oromos feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group , who make up about 6 % of the population , and who dominate the military , intelligence , trade , and politics .
The third reason for the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi .
Mr Meles , a former rebel leader , was Ethiopia &apos;s Prime Minister for 17 years until his death from an unpublicised disease in 2012 .
He was seen as a tactical genius , a man who could think around corners .
Analysts say that he was particularly adept at seeing early signs of discontent and using special envoys to manipulate opponents and render them harmless .
&quot; The current regime lacks this basic skill , &quot; said Mr Abdi , a conflict analyst .
Ethiopia &apos;s new prime minister , Hailemariam Desalegn , has been chosen to take over from Mr Meles for relatively obscure reasons .
Unlike Mr Meles , who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia , Mr Hailemariam comes from the south .
Analysts say that he does not have the confidence of the Tigray @-@ controlled security services .
Many fear that the result will be more bloodshed .
The last time Ethiopia experienced such a turmoil was in 2005 , after thousands protested against elections that , according to analysts , appeared to have been botched by the government and then stolen .
During the raids that followed , many protesters were killed , though fewer than in recent months , and that period of unrest passed relatively quickly .
Development experts praised Ethiopia &apos;s leaders for their visionary infrastructure planning , such as the new commuter train , and for their measurable progress in poverty reduction .
Obviously , however , this has not prevented the Ethiopian Government &apos;s internal resentment from intensifying .
And it is taking on a dangerous ethnic form .
Last month , protesters in Gondar , an Amharic city , attacked Tigray @-@ led businesses , and hatred of the Tigray is becoming increasingly common in social media .
Analysts say that the protests are putting the US and other Western allies in a strange position .
The American Government used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighbouring Somalia , although it recently announced that it had closed that base .
While the West clearly wants to support democracy , it does not want its ally to collapse in an already volatile area .
&apos;This , &apos; said Mr Abdi , &apos; is a very thin balancing act . &apos;
Donald Trump declares his claim that Obama founded ISIS was &quot; sarcasm .
Donald J. Trump tried on Friday to dispel the last controversy surrounding his campaign , saying that his repeated claim that President Obama and Hillary Clinton were the &quot; founders &quot; of the Islamic State terrorist group was not meant seriously .
This clarification raised new questions about the Republican presidential candidate &apos;s communication skills , whether he is able to communicate clearly and understandably with the American public .
It also puts his comrades @-@ in @-@ arms , who strive to defend him during an eventful period , in the peculiar position of having to explain statements that he might not have meant .
After hinting at a campaign event on Wednesday evening , Mr. Trump backtracked on Thursday &apos;s claim , insisting in interviews that he really had no intention of suggesting that the president and Mrs. Clinton had created ISIS .
But in an early morning tweet on Friday , Mr. Trump said he was simply sarcastic .
The tweet was the opposite of the previous day , when Mr. Trump said in a series of interviews that he meant the charge entirely seriously .
When conservative radio announcer Hugh Hewitt wanted to help Mr. Trump tone down the statement a little by reminding him that Mr. Obama wants to destroy ISIS , the Republican presidential candidate did not want to know about it .
The last storm of criticism rammed down on Mr. Trump , while he tried to shift his campaign &apos;s focus to the economy on account of falling polling numbers .
Mr. Trump and Mrs. Clinton delivered speeches on the state of the economy in Michigan this week .
On Friday , Mr Trump tried to return to the subject .
Mentioning via Twitter , he warned that Mrs. Clinton &apos;s proposals would lead to higher taxes , and that he had found her speech boring .
Mr. Trump has already advanced sarcasm in his defense .
At the end of July , he attracted strong criticism when he said that Russians should hack Mrs. Clinton &apos;s emails , but he later said , &quot; Of course , I meant that sarcastically . &quot;
This method allows Mr. Trump to shift the linguistic boundaries of politics , and then , if necessary , to row back .
&quot; I think it is one of his methods to test how certain messages are received by his fans , how they arrive , and then , if necessary , to &quot; clarify &quot; them depending on how the reaction turns out . &quot; said Ruth Sherman , a communications expert who monitors the language of both candidates .
However , I also believe that he is clever enough to keep his statements vague enough to allow them to be interpreted in various ways .
Instead of softening the tone for the presidential election , Mr Trump has adopted an even more corrosive tone , as his poll numbers have fallen further .
A new survey released on Friday by NBC / Wall Street Journal / Marist showed a lead in the states of North Carolina , Virginia , Colorado , and a head @-@ to @-@ head race in Florida .
While Mr. Trump generally tries not to apologize for his provocative statements , he often accuses his critics of distorting his statements or misreading his humor .
But , as he draws more attention in the final months of his presidential campaign , Mr. Trump &apos;s jokes have put his loyal comrades in the uncomfortable position of having to stand by him , however provocative his statements may be .
Rudolph W. Giuliani , a former mayor of New York and one of Trump &apos;s most prominent advocates , worked hard today to defend the candidate in a CNN interview on Thursday .
&quot; I believe that what he is saying are legitimate political comments , &quot; Mr. Giuliani said , so he was asked the truth of Mr. Trump &apos;s statements whether Mr. Obama and Mrs. Clinton had founded the Islamic State .
In this sense , it is true that , before Obama , ISIS was an almost unknown , small organization , he called it backbenchers , completely wrong , and it happened because he withdrew troops from Iraq .
Most mainstream Republicans try to argue that the Obama administration , in which Mrs. Clinton served as Secretary of State , allowed ISIS to spread by failing to aggressively control the situation in the Middle East .
Before Friday &apos;s election campaign in Pennsylvania , Mr Trump continued his attacks on the media , accusing them of harping on every word he said and biased against him .
He mocked the &quot; poor , wretched &quot; television experts who are trying to understand him and said , &quot; You can &apos;t ! &quot;
Some Democrats mocked Mr. Trump &apos;s apology as yet another demonstration that he was unfit for the presidency .
Once pushed out of the market on price , Café in Greenpoint comes back
Verb Cafe was a shabby cafe in Williamsburg , where you could only pay in cash , which did not have Wi @-@ Fi but served good coffee for 15 years .
Of course , its Bedford Avenue retail front has been crowded out by prices .
The Soap Cherie shop , which replaced Verb in the summer of 2014 , sells soap in the form of cupcakes .
Locals mourned it as the last loss in a gentrifying city .
The artist Molly Crabapple wrote on Twitter , &quot; I know New York is change , but I still can &apos;t believe that CBGB is dead , Chelsea Hotel is excluded , and Verb is now a soap shop . &quot;
But if New York is change , so is reinvention .
A revived Verb Cafe opened last November in Greenpoint , less than a mile north of its original location .
The new verb has Wi @-@ Fi and accepts credit cards , but still has some of the same staff and a similarly simple atmosphere .
The coffee is also still good .
The new owner of the verb is Cisco Rodriguez , a long @-@ time employee of the old café , who is the owner and manager of the new café .
He began working at Verb in 2001 and stayed there until the end .
When a client offered to provide him with funds for a new branch , he was excited to do so , he said .
Rodriguez , 36 , retained many things .
Verb uses the same distributor for the bagels bought the same espresso machine model .
It even uses the same lamps from the old verb .
But Rodriguez said that he also wanted to experiment .
He introduced new ingredients .
The menu includes sandwiches with bacon and cheese and there are garnishes such as capers and sour onions .
There are natural rice dishes .
The cafe no longer serves beer , but fresh juices are available .
After nine months , Rodriguez said he had noticed a steady stream of old regular customers .
&quot; Many old customers have also been displaced by prices from Williamsburg , &quot; he said .
On a Sunday recently , Rebecca Oliveira was one such customer .
Oliveira , 34 , used to live in Williamsburg and visited the verb regularly .
Even after she moved to Greenpoint , she would take the road .
After the verb had closed , she gave up drinking coffee for a while , she said .
&quot; I realized it was about the coffee and the culture in the verb that I liked , &quot; she said .
Now she drinks coffee again , even though that day she ordered a Blended Chai Tea instead of her usual Iced Coffee , which is another new addition .
Tom Rosenthal has been another long @-@ standing and loyal customer since the beginning of the verb in 2003 .
He went there before work and inevitably ordered the same thing .
&quot; I arrived at quarter past seven , every day like a Swiss pocket watch and they prepare my Everything Bagel with butter , &quot; he said .
Photo Rodriguez said he wanted to experiment and add new ingredients to the menu .
Today Rosenthal still gets his usual order , but sometimes he changes his Everything Bagel with bacon , egg and cheese .
Rodriguez said that he did not resent the fact that the soap business had taken over the old business space .
In fact , the owners of Soap Cherie offered to produce a special verbs soap with the café &apos;s cold @-@ brewed coffee as an ingredient .
&quot; I think we will respond to their offer , &quot; said Rodriguez .
And the traditional Polish residents of Greenpoint have also accepted the café .
A new customer has translated the menu into Polish , and Rodriguez said he plans to issue it soon , making his new neighbours feel welcome .
The location also has other benefits .
A local juice shop would like to fill the cold @-@ brewed coffee in the bottle and sell it .
There is a chance that the cafe will expand to a neighbouring building .
For many customers , a new verb is enough to get their old favorites .
Joseph Witt was a regular customer and said he was destroyed on the ground when the cafe closed .
When the new café opened , Whitt said that going into the café and ordering a new one felt like coming home .
&quot; I had to smell that , &quot; he said .
The depressing dinner of the economic crisis in &quot; a plentiful meal &quot;
In March 1933 , shortly after rising to the presidency , Franklin Delano Roosevelt had lunch at the Oval Office .
For gourmets , President Roosevelt had a penchant for sophisticated Fifth Avenue delicacies such as pâte de foie gras and Maryland water tortoise soup .
His menu that day was a little more modest : filled eggs in tomato sauce , potato puree and , as a dessert , a plum pudding .
&quot; It was an act of culinary solidarity with people who were suffering , &quot; said Jane Ziegelman .
Her husband Andrew Coe added , &quot; It was also a message to Americans about how they should eat . &quot;
The couple live in Brooklyn Heights and are both food historians .
Coe &apos;s last book , &quot; Chop Suey , &quot; was about Chinese cuisine in the US , while Ziegelman &apos;s book , &quot; 97 Orchard , &quot; talks about living in a home on the Lower East Side from a food perspective .
Her latest collaboration , &quot; A decent meal , &quot; which will be published by Harper Verlag on Tuesday , illustrates the history of American cuisine during the Great Depression .
They showed culinary solidarity when they met a reporter at Eisenberg &apos;s Sandwich Shop for dinner , a small , no @-@ frills snack in the Flatiron District , which has been in business since the 1929 stock market crash .
Ziegelman , 54 , ordered a fresh cheese sandwich with olive pieces , while Coe , 57 , turkey with potato puree and vegetable mix ate .
When the reporter ordered hackroasts , the couple found it suitable for a discussion about eating in the Great Depression era .
&quot; Rich foods were very popular , &quot; Ziegelman said .
There was peanut bread , liver cheese and bean bread .
They were made from an ingredient and something cheap to stretch out .
Imagine eating so many peanuts that they serve as dinner .
Coe grunt .
&quot; It must have laid in the stomach like lead , &quot; he said .
In the years before the Great Depression , the table in an American household , especially in rural areas , was an all @-@ you @-@ can @-@ eat buffet .
Women &apos;s teams cooked for male field workers and freshly baked pâté was served for breakfast , lunch and dinner .
It was the Americans who sent food to hungry Europeans during World War I . &quot; A Square Meal &quot; records the paths that the country has taken to stop being the land of plenty .
&quot; It was a time when food became a central , tense issue for Americans , &quot; Coe explained why he and his wife wanted to write about it .
The new budget was just as tight : mysterious dishes such as bread and casseroles became staples , casseroles as a &quot; wonderful way to recycle leftovers , &quot; Ziegelman noted , as chefs could hide unsavoury ingredients under a creamy sauce .
Fresh fruit has been replaced by cheaper dry fruit .
Meat , which for years was the focal point of American cuisine , became a rare luxury .
Strange mixtures have been tried , as a calorie @-@ rich and nourishing satisfaction has taken precedence over taste or even common sense .
While researching for the book , which also includes recipes , brick man prepared a dish from that era , baked onion with peanut butter .
&quot; It was not a popular addition at lunch time , &quot; Coe says .
Ziegelmann goes on to say , &quot; It was surreal . &quot;
Peanut butter and fried onions do not match each other .
It was typical of many of the home @-@ economics recipes .
As never before or since , household economists - including Louise Stanley , head of the Federal Bureau of Home Economics between 1923 and 1943 - drove the country &apos;s eating habits in this way .
By publishing recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines , they encouraged women to become &quot; housewives &quot; and to rise to the challenge of turning pamphlets like creamy spaghetti with carrots into delicious meals .
&quot; A Square Meal &quot; is a festival of historical delights .
Particularly tasty are the reports of the government &apos;s response to the starving citizens , such as President Herbert Hoover &apos;s Lass @-@ mich @-@ Kuchen @-@ Essen attitude .
While publicly praising the simple Iowa farm kitchen of his kitchen , he fed like the multi @-@ million dollar man of the world he has become .
&quot; He liked continental cuisine such as fish with cucumber sauce , &quot; Coe said .
He ate in an almost gold @-@ plated dining room and wore a tuxedo .
It was splendidly out of touch .
President Roosevelt might have made the same mistake if his wife , Eleanor , had not asked him to set an example with his stomach .
As described in the book , the hiring of a housekeeper with no interest in tastes by Mrs Roosevelt meant that the White House produced the most dull meal in Washington , but also one of the most dismal prepared . &quot;
Many of the Great Depression @-@ era ways of eating were discarded once the country got back on its feet .
The legacy lies in our continued focus on calories and food , Ziegelman said , as well as how science was applied to food .
In writing the book , the couple claimed to have understood better the eating habits of Ziegelman &apos;s mother @-@ in @-@ law - for example , how she could not throw away food .
&quot; She was really afraid to waste food , &quot; Coe said .
Ziegelman remembered : &quot; She actually made people sick . &quot;
There was the windbag incident .
After the plates had been cleared at Eisenberg &apos;s , they and Coe pulled out a dessert they had prepared at home : the plum dessert that President Roosevelt ate for lunch .
&quot; It &apos;s called Prune Whip , &quot; Ziegelman said , adding that it was a common trick to give modest recipes a chic name .
There was no beaten cream , just plums , some flour , sugar , water and cinnamon .
Everyone dipped a spoon a bit grudgingly in the tough brown glibber .
Amazingly , it did not taste bad .
Coe caught up three times .
Like a Can @-@ Do budgeman , he said to his wife , &quot; A few chopped walnuts would help . &quot;
Bombs killed : He was the hero of Aleppo
He put his own life on the line to help others : Khaled Omar .
He was the hero of Aleppo : Khaled Omar dedicated his life to the people of Syria .
He risked everything to save the lives of others .
Now the 30 @-@ year @-@ old has even died in a barrel bomb attack by the Assad regime .
Omar was a member of the &quot; White Helmets , &quot; a civil protection group that , according to Bild newspaper , has so far saved nearly 60,000 lives .
2 900 volunteers risk their own lives to move people out of bombed houses and to provide first aid in the war zone .
They are the heroes of the war in Syria .
Omar was the face of the group : a video of the defender showing him in an 11 @-@ hour rescue of a baby from the rubble of a house went around the world in 2014 .
It made the Syrian a shining symbol in the horror of war .
As a hero , however , he never saw himself , according to the image : &quot; For me , this is the real Jihad . &quot;
&quot; When I die saving lives , I think God sees me as a martyr . &quot;
Shortly before Omar himself fell victim to an attack , he spoke in a video about the latest bombing in Syria .
The helicopters dropped four barrel bombs over the Alzadia district , one of which was filled with chlorine gas .
One woman and two children died and seven people are suffering from breathing difficulties .
&quot; We are now cleaning up the poisonous remains of the bomb so that children do not play with it , &quot; the picture quoted his last words before he died .
The Assad regime &apos;s lethal bomb was supposed to hit terrorists .
Greenland Shark : The oldest vertebrate is nearly 400 years old
A rare sight .
Greenland sharks tend to surface only in winter .
This shark was allowed back into the sea after an investigation on board the research vessel Sanna .
Born in 1624 , he floats through the North Atlantic at just over 1 km / h - to this day .
Greenland sharks do not grow up until the age of 150 .
The Greenland shark swims gently along the bottom of the North Atlantic , reaching an average distance of just 1,220 metres in an hour .
Only when it comes down to it does the five @-@ metre @-@ long animal accelerate to a whopping 2.6 km / h - and at this top speed is half as fast as a seal .
This slow @-@ moving lifestyle , however , seems to be a perfect recipe for old age .
Julius Nielsen of the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues report in the scientific journal about a Greenland shark that could be 392 years old .
&quot; Madness , &quot; says Alexander Scheuerlein of the Max Planck Institute for Demographic Research in Rostock , commenting on this life span , which is a world record for vertebrates .
To be sure , the evolutionary biologist long suspected Greenland sharks of becoming stone @-@ old .
But the evidence was missing .
Greenland sharks are hard to observe , as they mainly live in the Arctic Ocean off the sparsely populated coasts of Canada , Greenland , Norway and Spitsbergen .
Because they prefer water temperatures of around six degrees Celsius , they usually appear on the surface only in winter .
Researchers know very little about the lifestyle of Greenland sharks .
They measured their slow @-@ motion speed when they equipped six animals with a transmitter in front of Spitzbergen .
Yet these sharks prey : in the stomach of one animal , researchers found the remains of a seal , another had swallowed the jaw bone of a young polar bear .
They may hunt sleeping animals or patrol the bottom of the Arctic Ocean looking for corpses torpedoing down from higher layers of water .
Julius Nielsen and his colleagues now studied 28 Greenland sharks that caught fishermen off Greenland or Spitsbergen between 2010 and 2013 as a by @-@ catch from the depths of the North Atlantic .
The smallest shark was just 81 cm long , while the largest was 502 cm long .
In order to determine the age of the animals , they analysed the lens nucleus of the sharks using the carbon @-@ 14 method .
This center of the eye lens is formed before the sharks are born , and the proteins contained in it are not renewed later .
The two smallest sharks had a striking amount of carbon @-@ 14 in the lens core .
Their birth should therefore be after the early 1960 &quot; s , when nuclear weapons tests emitted large quantities of this radioactive carbon into the atmosphere .
By contrast , in the third smallest animal , 220 centimeters in length , the lens nucleus contained a small surplus of carbon 14 from nuclear weapons testing , which is likely to have been its 50th birthday when it was studied in 2012 .
By contrast , all the larger Greenland sharks had normal carbon 14 in their lensing core , which is produced by cosmic radiation in the atmosphere .
Indeed , for a 493 @-@ centimeter Greenland shark , the carbon 14 clock showed an age of 335 , while the record shark , at 502 centimeters , is likely to be as old as 392 .
It was well known that Greenland shark females only have offspring when they are longer than four metres .
Now the researchers were able to assign an age to the length .
Since one of the animals , at 392 centimetres , was probably on the verge of maturing and its age was determined at 156 , it appears that breeding Greenland sharks takes at least a century and a half .
That , too , should be a world record for vertebrates at the moment .
It is no accident that such methus alemes mainly live in icy waters .
The previous record holder , a 211 @-@ year @-@ old Greenland whale with a 120 @-@ year @-@ old Harpoon tip on its neck , was also caught off Alaska .
Due to the low temperatures , the organism of the animals living there is often also on fire .
So they mature later - and age more slowly .
In addition , in order to keep warm in cold water , the animals often become particularly large .
This is because the volume grows much faster than its surface , through which the animal loses heat .
The heat loss of one gram of mouse is therefore much greater than that of one gram of elephant .
Another advantage : they have fewer enemies .
&quot; So a smaller animal lives more dangerously and should concentrate on having as many offspring as possible as early on , &quot; explains evolutionary biologist Scheuerlein .
A very large animal , on the other hand , should invest its resources in a long life .
Construction Land in Double Pack
At its most recent meeting , the Municipal Council focused on construction @-@ related issues .
It was with relief that the panel received Mayor Robert Putz &apos;s announcement that &quot; the marketing of the recently designated residential areas can finally begin . &quot;
After clarifying the questions of plots of land , parcelling and development as well as applications for surveying , nothing more stands in the way of selling the plots of land to interested parties in the residential areas of &quot; Street Path &quot; and &quot; Schönau West &quot; ( area Binderstraße - section 1 ) .
The municipal council is convinced that the areas in the rural and quiet residential community of Schönau appeal to young families and well @-@ equipped senior citizens alike .
It has been said that those who wish to build can report to the town hall from now on , and the local council is expected to discuss the allocation of the plots at its September meeting .
In order also to be able to respond to requests for the establishment of further businesses in connection with the creation of jobs , the municipal council decided to amend the land @-@ use plan , which was only redrawn up in the spring of this year , in some areas .
In the sub @-@ time zone , for example , the industrial area already designated there will be extended by two plots in the direction of State Road 2112 .
Frankfurt benefits from Brexit
The city on the river Main therefore has the best chance of attracting jobs and companies from London , competing with Paris , Dublin and Luxembourg .
&quot; It is very likely that Frankfurt will benefit the most from the Brexit vote , &quot; says Michael Voigtländer , Head of Financial Markets and Real Estate Markets at the IW .
In the wake of the Brexit referendum , it is uncertain whether financial institutions can continue to operate from London across the EU .
For the so @-@ called EU passport , they have so far been granted admission in Great Britain .
Large US banks are taking advantage of this .
Several banks have already announced that they will move jobs .
The lobby association &quot; Frankfurt Main Finance &quot; expects 10,000 new jobs to be created on the Main river within five years .
For Frankfurt , the IW argues , the headquarters of the European Central Bank ( ECB ) , which combines responsibility for monetary policy and supervision of the eurozone &apos;s largest banks , as well as other important authorities , such as the European Insurance Supervision EIOPA and the Risk Board ESRB .
While the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development ( OECD ) is headquartered in Paris , it is less important to the financial industry than the ECB .
&quot; Proximity to the central bank is important for banks , as it enables them to communicate directly with supervisors , &quot; says IW professor Voigtländer .
Luxembourg is home to a large fund industry but , like Dublin , is worse off in terms of infrastructure .
Frankfurt is much easier to reach thanks to the large airport .
In addition , the city points with easily available commercial properties .
&quot; It is not at all easy to find high @-@ quality offices in Paris , &quot; says Voigtländer .
On the Seine , first @-@ class commercial real estate rents are also 50 percent higher than on the Main .
In addition , Frankfurt offers a better quality of life than its competitors thanks to good medical care and infrastructure , as well as less crime .
The city is ranked seventh in the Mercer management consultancy &apos;s ranking , 19th in Luxembourg , 33rd in Dublin and 37th in Paris .
Even if quality of life is a matter of preferences : &quot; With its already strong position as a financial centre for the European single market , Frankfurt could attract more banks and investors , &quot; the IW concludes .
But London , despite the Brexit vote , will remain Europe &apos;s main financial center , economic forecasters say .
This is also borne out by the balance of power : according to figures from Landesbank Helaba , around 144,000 people worked in the banking industry in London at the end of 2015 , 62500 in Frankfurt .
Gilead gets legal costs from the hepatitis C patent dispute with Merck
A U.S. District Court ruled that Gilead Sciences Inc is entitled to a refund of legal costs incurred by it as a result of the Hepatits C dispute with pharmaceutical company Merck &amp; Co Inc .
In June , Gilead was released from $ 200 million in compensation for infringement of two Merck patents related to Gilead &apos;s blockbuster drugs , Sovaldi and Harvoni , after a US judge revealed a pattern of bad behavior by Mercks , including perjury and other unethical acts .
When the case was brought on Thursday , US Chief Justice Beth Labson Freeman said that Gilead is entitled to forgive the costs incurred in defending the case .
Merck is trying to catch up with Gilead , which dominates the market of a new generation of hepatitis C drugs that can cure more than 90 % of patients with liver disease .
The case dates back to 2013 , when Gilead and Merck took each other to court and claimed ownership of laboratory work based on Sofosbuvir , the active ingredient in Gilead &apos;s drugs .
