Clintons earn $ 10.75 million in 2015 and pay 34.2 % federal taxes .
Hillary Clinton released her 2015 tax return on Friday , which yielded an income of $ 10.75 million for the Democratic presidential candidate and her husband , and an effective federal tax rate of 34.2 % .
In 2015 , the Clinton administration donated $ 1 million for charitable causes , mainly to the Clinton Foundation ; former President Bill Clinton raised almost $ 5.3 million in speech fees ; former Secretary of State Simon &amp; Schuster reported an income of $ 3 million for her book on her tenure at the State Department .
Clinton &apos;s running mate , Virginia Senator Tim Kaine , along with his wife Anne Holton , released his tax returns over the past decade .
They paid an effective federal tax rate of 20.3 % in 2015 .
&quot; Hillary Clinton and Tim Kaine continue to set standards in terms of financial transparency , &quot; Clinton &apos;s campaign assistant Jennifer Palmieri announced in a statement .
In stark contrast , Donald Trump is hiding behind false excuses and backsliding on his previous promises to publish his tax returns .
It is customary for US presidential candidates to publish their tax returns , even though they are not required to do so by law .
Trump , a New York businessman , and his lawyers have cited a tax review by the tax authorities as a reason for refusing .
&quot; The ball is in your court , &quot; Clinton &apos;s campaign assistant , Ian Sams , wrote on Twitter about the publication of the Democratic presidential candidate .
On Thursday , Michael Cohen , Trump &apos;s special adviser , told CNN that he would not allow Trump to publish anything until the tax reviews had been completed .
Trump &apos;s critics , including the Republican presidential candidate Mitt Romney in 2012 , have already announced that his refusal to do so raises questions about assets , his donations to charities , his business practices , and various other ties , particularly with Russia .
Clinton has already pounced on the issue , posting a video on the Internet on Friday in which top Republicans call on Trump to publish his tax returns .
On Thursday , she also raised the issue during a speech on the economy in Michigan .
&quot; He refuses to do what any other presidential candidate has done in recent decades and publish his tax returns . &quot; She said to the crowd .
Politico has reported that Trump paid little or no tax for two years during the 1990 &quot; s , and one New York Times economic journalist quoted a number of tax lawyers and advisers on Friday who said that might still be the case .
Federal taxes have become an issue in the election campaign .
Clinton supports a scheme named after the billionaire and investor Warren Buffett , which would ensure that people earning more than $ 1 million pay a tax rate of at least 30 % .
President Obama also supports the proposal .
At a campaign rally for Hillary Clinton last week in Omaha , Nebraska , Buffett , whose Berkshire Hathaway industrial conglomerate is based here , called for Trump to meet to exchange tax returns .
Buffett said he had also been subject to the IRS &apos;s tax review , and Trump was &quot; afraid &quot; of voters , not tax authorities .
Clinton &apos;s campaign released tax returns back to 2007 .
The Clintons , now living in Chappaqua , New York , paid an average effective federal tax rate of about 32 % between 2007 and 2014 and an effective combined tax rate of about 40.5 % .
The Clinton tax return of 2015 showed that , unlike most Americans , they received only $ 100 of their income in wages .
Their principal investment was a low @-@ cost index fund , which taxed the Clinton dividends and $ 109,000 in earnings .
