Condoms with chilli powder , fireworks promote Tanzania &apos;s elephant protection .
Conservationists in Tanzania use an unorthodox species to deter elephants from going to man @-@ made settlements - they throw condoms filled with chile powder at them .
The method has proven effective , and the Honeyguide Foundation , which came up with the idea years ago , has stepped up its promotion , together with the US Conservation Agency , by training volunteers in villages in northern Tanzania to use a non @-@ violent , four @-@ step method to protect their homes and crops , while not injuring animals .
Before that , many spears used to defend themselves .
Friday is World Telephone Day , dedicated to animal welfare .
&quot; Since we developed the ... Toolkit , we have seen a change of attitude within these communities , which are much more confident that they can keep the elephants off their fields without harming the elephant , &quot; said Honeyguide Damian Bell &apos;s managing director in a message .
The first two steps include the lighting of the elephant with a torch and the blowing into a horn .
If he is not deterred , a so @-@ called &quot; chile cloud &quot; will be thrown .
Mixed with earth , chile powder is packed together with a fireworks body into a condom , the end of which is turned to the fuse .
When lit , the condom bursts with a bang and sprays fine dust into the air on chilli powder .
A touch usually enough already to drive the elephant out .
A final possibility is a shooter shooting a gold gun into the air , causing a loud , bright explosion .
