Jewish director breaks up Berlin Hotel because Israel &apos;s pre @-@ election &quot; Arab &quot; call was removed - RT News
A French director with Jewish roots set off a media uproar after he revealed that the Kempinski Bristol Hotel in Berlin had not listed an Israeli pre @-@ election code because Arab guests had &quot; requested &quot; it , according to one of its staff member .
Claude Lanzmann , author of the Holocaust documentary &quot; Shoah , &quot; dropped his anger at the Kempinski Bristol Hotel in Berlin by writing an open letter to the German newspaper FAZ .
During his last stay , Lanzmann tried to find Israel on the hotel &apos;s country code .
However , the country was not listed between the countries that can be called directly from the hotel room .
How is it possible in 2016 , in Berlin , the capital of the new Germany , that Israel was eliminated and deleted ?
wrote Lanzmann .
Instead , Kempinksi Bristol offers an option to call Israel via its own call center .
Looking for an explanation , the director turned to the hotel reception .
The response he received there , as Lanzmann wrote , &quot; shocked him . &quot;
The hotel employee said that the measure was a &quot; deliberate decision of the management of Kempinski Hotels . &quot;
The reason behind this triggered even more anger in the director .
&quot; The majority of our guests are Arabs and they have asked for the prefix to be deleted , &quot; the employee of Lanzmann was quoted .
The Israeli Ambassador to Germany , Yakov Hadas @-@ Handelsman , called this a &quot; great shame , &quot; reports the Süddeutsche Zeitung .
We were shocked and dismayed by this event .
That is a real shame .
The fact that this has happened in Germany in the very same hotel chain is an even greater disgrace .
This need no explanation .
We expect the hotel to &quot; draw the right conclusions , &quot; said the official .
The incident triggered quite a lot of response on the Internet , where people called it a scandal .
Some suggested that the Kempinski Hotel had &quot; succumbed &quot; to the alleged demands of Arab guests .
&quot; Shame on you , &quot; said another speech , pointing out that the hotel , located on the noble Kurfürstendamm , is close to a synagogue .
The hotel quickly dismissed all accusations and called the incident an &quot; oversight &quot; and &quot; apologized &quot; to Lanzmann , Der Spiegel reports .
&quot; There was never a direct order , &quot; the Süddeutsche Zeitung quoted a spokesman of the Kempinski Hotel , &quot; not to include Israel in the quick list .
It adds that the country code has now been added .
