Haigerloch : Pilgrimage to the Gate of Mercy
The ministers from the Eyachtal @-@ Haigerloch St. Anna spiritual unit were on a four @-@ day pilgrimage from Villingen to Freiburg .
Together , four stages were completed .
In order to cover the period leading up to the next pilgrimage of all ministers in probably two years , the St. Anna Round of Ministers has decided to prepare and conduct a pilgrimage lasting several days .
Various pilgrimage destinations were examined and finally the bishop &apos;s town of Freiburg was chosen , where this year , on the occasion of the Holy Year of Mercy , a special pilgrimage destination was offered on the occasion of the gate of mercy at the Fribourg Cathedral , which was opened for this purpose .
16 minis from Bittelbronn , Gruol , Haigerloch and holy rooms set out .
The evening before , the parish priest , Storost , sent the pilgrims to a small celebration in St. Anna , blessed the cross and blessed the pilgrim blessing .
From Horb there was a train ride to the starting point of Villingen , where there is also a Cathedral of Our Lady and so the pilgrimage path from the Cathedral was started .
The individual day tours were each framed by a short impulse in the morning and in the evening with various prayers , songs and writings .
On the way , the minis stopped at field crosses , chapels or churches to sing together a song from specially compiled pilgrimage song booklet .
For the overnight stays the dormitories of the local pastors were available .
At the stages Alexandra Burkhardt and Heidi Faller provided for a tasty as well as invigorating dinner and breakfast .
On the second day we continued via Furtwangen to Gütenbach .
The next day they started the stage to St. Peter , which was the hardest part of the way , because in the heat of the day they had to descend about 500 metres and then climb again .
In the evening , the deserved reward was a shared barbecue at the bathing pond .
After the morning impulse on the fourth day of pilgrimage in the imposing convent church of St. Peter , we went on the final stage to Freiburg .
The Minis arrived at the Freiburger Münster in the late afternoon , visibly relieved and happy , and crossed the gate of mercy .
With a small impulse God was thanked here .
Cooperative Markus Obert welcomed the minis who arrived at the pilgrim &apos;s destination at the evening mass in the Cathedral .
After the service , pilgrims were able to visit the sacristy and high altar .
The next day there was still time for the Breisgau metropolis .
In the afternoon we went back by train to Horb .
In the end , all participants agreed that the days were marked by spirituality and a strong sense of community .
Scot Callum Skinner storms home as Britons get gold for cycling .
Scotland &apos;s Callum Skinner raced last night at the men &apos;s team sprint at the Velodrom in Rio , as the British team defended the London 2012 title .
The 23 @-@ year @-@ old from Glasgow took on the anchor role his compatriot Sir Chris Hoy had taken on , and the boy made the legend proud as he stormed home to claim victory from New Zealand &apos;s favorites .
England claimed a shocking victory four years ago , while Hoy won the fifth of six Olympic gold medals .
They repeated the trick after finishing only a modest sixth place at the London World Railway Championships in March , despite Hoy &apos;s resignation .
The problem between Beijing and London was the replacement of driver Jamie Staff .
They did so in time for it to appear .
Hoy &apos;s retirement created a gap that Kian Emadi and Matt Crampton tried to fill .
Skinner was the man they stayed with when they saw potential in the Scotsman that has now developed .
On the other hand , Kenny - who won with Hoy four years ago - and Skinner set an Olympic record in qualifying rounds , but in the standard laps New Zealand won in the first round .
And the British trio won the duel with gold .
On the other hand , his lap was short , but Kenny brought the team to the front and Skinner held it up .
A change of strategy was a major part of the transformation , in which Hinder drove in a higher gear to slow it down and allow Kenny , and especially Skinner , to keep up the pace .
Hoy looked on from his position as a BBC expert and caught the eye of Skinner , Kenny and Hindu as they rose on the podium .
The 23 @-@ year @-@ old Glasgow skinner said : &quot; It is a flattering comparison . &quot;
I am only here to do my best and make a name for myself .
In the end , we set an Olympic record and beat the World Champions .
It was simply incredible .
There is no better way to win this .
After the 2012 triumph side by side with Kennys and Hoys , Hinder admitted that , after a weak start , he deliberately fell on the track .
He later withdrew that statement , and there was no objection from England &apos;s rivals .
There was no such problem with such an overwhelming victory this time .
On the other hand , it said : &apos; It feels like London with all the GB flags in the gallery . &apos;
We have come together as a team over the last three months .
We lost so much on so many world titles that it was incredible to win the Olympics again .
This is an event , a gold medal for the nation , won seven out of 10 titles in both Beijing and London .
If this is a barometer of our progress over the last five months , then successful five days in the Velodrom are waiting for us .
With Kennys &quot; form , it is possible that he will repeat Hoy &apos;s victory of three Olympic gold medals in a competition .
For Kenny - who is exactly 12 years younger than Hoy , who was also born on 23 March ( a seemingly sacred date for British sport ; that day Steve Redgrave , Mo Farah , and Roger Bannister were also born ) - that would mean an yield of six gold medals and one silver medal .
That would be like Hoy &apos;s .
Kenny will be next in the sprint , which starts today and will go over three days .
The 28 @-@ year @-@ old from Bolton said : &apos; I only enjoy this for the moment &apos; .
The team event is always best .
You can win it with your colleagues .
It feels a bit lonely to win alone .
On the other hand , he said , &quot; If he wins two more gold medals , he should be beaten as a knight . &quot;
It was the only medal competition of the day , but there was more good news for England .
Sir Bradly Wiggins , Ed Clancy , Steven Burke and Owain Doull qualified with the fastest performance in the four @-@ mile race .
They arrived at the finish in 3 : 51.942 .
The world record which won gold in London in 2012 was 3 : 51.659 .
The first and final round ( 22.42 ) will take place today on the second day of the competition , where Wiggins will certainly be the focus .
He argued with officials yesterday before the qualification when officials called him to measure his body size .
Laura Trott , Joanna Rowsell Shand , Elinor Barker and Katie Archibald of Milngavie advanced in world record time at 4 : 13.260 in the corresponding women &apos;s competition , which will continue and end tomorrow .
The UK team relies on its strong rail team to dominate the middle period of the Olympic Games and win a host of medals .
After a truly extraordinary portrayal of absolute dominance in Beijing and London , expectations for Rio have been reduced .
Dramas played out in the background , such as technical director Shane Sutton &apos;s resignation in April amid accusations of sexism and mobbing , as well as the retirement of figures such as Hoy and Victoria Pendleton .
Looking at the first evening of the Velodrom competition , however , it looks as if the now legendary reputation of GB , which reached its peak at the perfect moment , could be repeated .
Future of the Portland melt due to the suspension of the energy contract
The future of Portland &apos;s aluminium melting plant in Victoria - as well as hundreds of workers &apos; jobs - is at stake , as the plant operator will terminate the energy supply contract , cancelling all supply contracts , according to the supplying energy company .
That move followed the Victoria government &apos;s decision earlier this year not to give any more subsidies to operate the plant .
A 20 @-@ year subsidy will come to an end in November .
Up to 2000 jobs at the Alcoa plant in Portland are at risk .
No fewer than 2 000 jobs - both direct and indirect - could be put at risk by closure .
There could also be knock @-@ on effects , as the melt consumes about 10 % of Victoria &apos;s total electricity production .
In 2014 , Alcoa closed its Point Henry smelting plant , which led to the closure of the Anglesea power plant last year .
The Alcoa melting plant in Portland is losing money and is at risk of closure .
This move follows years of speculation about the plant &apos;s future , initially as a result of the strong Australian dollar , and most recently because of the plant &apos;s electricity price .
AGL , which supplies the large aluminium smelting plant with its Loy Yang A power plant in Latrobe Valley , announced that it expects three other owners to terminate their contracts .
The plant is majority owned by a joint venture between Alcoa and Alumina , with smaller shares held by CITIC and Marubeni Corp of Japan .
&quot; AGL expects the plant in Portland to continue to operate , which means further physical demand for electricity from the melt , &quot; the company said .
AGL also stated that the contracts were so @-@ called &quot; hedging transactions , &quot; which should have entered into force from November 2016 .
The contracts have a 12 @-@ month termination period , so they will end in 2017 .
&quot; Therefore , AGL expects the contracts to contribute to revenue in fiscal year 17 , &quot; said the electricity supplier .
All potential effects on AGL revenues from FY18 onwards are currently constrained by forecasts from the strong wholesale electricity derivatives markets .
AGL announced that it had already written off the value of the contracts in its annual statement of $ 187 million in anticipation of &quot; termination . &quot;
Alcoa said that the decision to award contracts does not affect the &quot; ability of Alcoas ... to operate the smelting or to provide electricity to the smelting plant . &quot;
The US company said that it signed a 20 @-@ year contract with Loy Yang in 2010 , which should have entered into force from November this year , though it still owes an explanation as to why it withdrew from the contract .
Analysts warn of the possible closure of the Portland melt shop in Victoria and the Tomago plant near Newcastle due to the poor economic conditions in the industry .
Referring to what analysts said earlier this week , Stephen Mikkelsen , Head of Operations , said Portland uses around 600 megawatts of electricity per year and Tomago around 900 megawatts of electricity per year .
Should both plants disappear from the market , demand in the &#91; electricity market &#93; would be significantly reduced .
And for us as electricity producers that would not be good , &quot; he said .
