Local law centres turn away 160,000 people a year .
More than 160,000 of the country &apos;s most vulnerable people are turned away each year by community law centers , while the industry prepares to face the impact of further cuts in funds on already overburdened transactions .
In Queensland , three out of five people - mostly the elderly , immigrants , needy workers , victims of violence , and those without the means for unjust deportations and the like - are already being turned away when they apply for free legal advice and assistance .
Local legal services , which are already overused , are preparing for further cuts .
From June next year , these legal centres are expected to lose a further 30 percent of their federal funds .
The director of the Queesland James Farrell community rights centres said that the latest survey of the National Association of Community Law Centres found that thousands of people are already turned away each year .
Farrell said that the situation would only get worse without repealing the federal government &apos;s decision .
&quot; Queensland &apos;s municipal law centers are chronically underfunded , which means that thousands of people are turned away from important services you need , &quot; he said .
People who leave violent relationships , people with unmanageable and stifling debts , families going through separation , workers who have been unfairly dismissed - all these people have problems of a legal nature and this survey shows that they cannot get the help they need .
From June 2017 , the federal government will cut funding by 30 % , which means that thousands of more vulnerable people from Queensland will be forced to cope with their legal problems without any help .
We call on the Federal Attorney @-@ General and Federal Justice Minister , as well as Queensland senators George Brandis , to lift these cuts immediately so that people can get the help they need in the event of legal problems .
Last year , the national government delivered on its promise to raise funds for legal assistance to the national average .
It is now time to look at the needs of community law centres and their client communities , as well as for the Palaszczuk government to invest in this important work .
