Berlin / Schwerin : Survey before Country Elections : SPD and CDU lose
In the upcoming elections in the federal states Mecklenburg @-@ Western Pomerania ( 4 September ) and Berlin ( 18 September ) , considerable losses for the ruling parties SPD and CDU are becoming apparent .
This was the finding of representative surveys conducted by the opinion research institute INSA for the &quot; Bild &quot; newspaper ( Friday ) .
While the red @-@ black coalition government in the north could continue to govern just a little further , according to the polls in Berlin this is not possible .
In both German states , however , the SPD would be the strongest party , and would thus have a good chance of retaining the head of government .
In Mecklenburg @-@ Western Pomerania , the SPD fell from 35.6 percent five years ago to 24 percent .
The party would thus be close to the CDU , which could return to 23 % , according to the survey .
Third place is disputed between the left and the AfD .
The left would be 19 % ( previously 18.4 % ) , and the AfD would be 19 % for the first time in the state parliament .
Despite slight losses , the Greens would return to the Schwerin parliament with 6 percent ( previously 8.7 percent ) .
The NPD and the FDP would not be represented in the state parliament with 3 percent each .
According to the poll , the SPD would only reach 23 % in Berlin &apos;s House of Deputies election ( election 2011 : 28.3 % ) .
The CDU only reached 18 percent , down from 23.4 percent .
It would still lag behind the Greens , at 19 % ( 2011 : 17.6 % ) , but ahead of the left , at 15 % ( previously 11.7 % ) .
The AfD would have 14 % representation in the Congress for the first time .
With 5 % , the FDP could hope for a return , whereas the pirates would miss out , unlike in 2011 .
Nokia 9000 Communicator : The First Smartphone
E @-@ mail and Internet in slow motion : 20 years ago , the Nokia Communicator came on the market .
The successors now dominate the world - its manufacturer suffered a disaster .
The device weighed almost half a kilogram and was more than four times as heavy as an iPhone 5 .
It was thicker and bigger , so it did not lie well in your hand .
On the contrary , it was pretty knockout .
The built @-@ in memory was eight megabytes in the beginning , which would be enough for about two selfs with high resolution today .
An iPhone now ships with at least 16 gigabytes .
Exactly 20 years ago , on August 15 , 1996 , the &quot; Nokia 9000 Communicator &quot; went into stores - and it was the first smartphone .
Lovers of these devices can still buy them on the Internet for a few euros , but they somehow date back to the Stone Age of the Internet .
But 20 years ago , the communicator was a sensation .
The Finnish manufacturer of mobile phones announced the product as a &quot; pocket @-@ sized office &quot; at the Cebit computer fair in Hanover a few months earlier .
In fact , the new mobile phone could for then standards a lot : SMS and e @-@ mails could be sent and received , even by fax was the communicator to reach .
Even HTML browser access to web pages was possible , though painfully slow .
A pocket calculator was available , a digital address book and an electronic calendar .
There was a small antenna , and the mobile phone could be opened similar to a laptop .
Then there was a small keyboard and a black @-@ and @-@ white screen .
The prize was rather proud : DM 2700 , or about EUR 1400 .
The average selling price of a smartphone in Germany in 2015 was 392 euros .
No one could have guessed in August 1996 that the communicator would be the beginning of the smart phone era .
Since then , everything has changed .
The clever phones are a success story , though not for Nokia .
The Finnish mobile phone sector experienced an unprecedented disaster , eventually being sold to Microsoft .
The market today is dominated by suppliers , all of whom came much later than Nokia .
Being online all the time , that &apos;s everyday life for a lot of people today .
In 2015 , there were nearly two billion smart phone users worldwide .
Some 1.4 billion devices have been sold , of which Samsung and Apple alone account for 555 million .
Worldwide sales of the equipment are around 400 billion euros .
On top of that , there are the well @-@ run businesses of the countless app providers and telecommunications companies .
A whole industry has come into being around the smart phone .
The decisive breakthrough to the mass market came only in early 2007 , when Apple CEO Steve Jobs announced the introduction of the iPhone on Mac @-@ World .
He promised three devices in one : a music player , a phone and an Internet communicator , all by touch screen easy to use .
Apple &apos;s triumphal march began , and the iPhone is still the company &apos;s most important product today .
Nokia , Motorola and Blackberry , which dominated the market , were left behind .
They eventually disappeared , Blackberry is struggling .
Apple and Asian suppliers such as Samsung are now in charge .
The Smartphone is taken for granted 20 years after its invention .
On average , every German now looks at his or her mobile phone 88 times a day .
&quot; We all need to learn to remove the smartphone , &quot; said Janina Kugel , who is responsible for human resources on the Siemens Board of Directors .
Permanent accessibility is now seen as both a curse and a blessing .
England Must Lead the Olympic Spirit and Expand Heathrow
Heathrow will bring renewal and prosperity not only to our local communities and to the whole of London , but to the whole country .
For me , this was the biggest attraction Heathrow , just as it was in London in 2012 , when we put a great deal of effort into ensuring that all our nations and regions benefited from the Games .
The Olympics brought great benefits to Stratford and the East End .
And we will do that again by creating new opportunities for local residents and companies near Heathrow .
For our local communities alone , we will already be creating 10,000 new apprenticeships , 40,000 new jobs and putting an end to youth unemployment in the airport environment .
As they were ahead of us in London in 2012 , there will be those who will think that the challenge of extension Heathrows is too great .
I have been told that England will never be ready for the Games and that we will make fools of ourselves on the world stage .
The doubters were wrong in 2012 , and they will be wrong with Heathrow .
There are always obstacles to overcome , but Heathrow answers every question put to it .
Like the Olympic Games , Heathrow is an infrastructure project for many , not for individuals .
Enlargement is an opportunity to create up to 180,000 new jobs , £ 211 billion in economic growth , and to leave a legacy of skills and employment both around the airport and across the UK .
We have a great team at Heathrow , which has spent £ 11 billion on infrastructure investment in time and budget , from the T5 - voted the world &apos;s best airport terminal for five consecutive years - to the T2 , built in the middle of the world &apos;s two busiest catwalks .
Now they stand ready to deliver a third catwalk , supported by £ 16 billion in private investment .
The London Games of 2012 were a great success for the UK , and I am confident that the expansion of Heathrow will be one as well .
It is time that we steered this Olympic spirit and extended Heathrow , while securing our future trade and creating a legacy of skills and employment of which England can be proud .
Lord Paul Deighton is Chairman of the Heathrow Board and former Commercial Secretary to the Treasury .
Adblock Plus , Facebook in the &quot; Cat and Mouse Game &quot; regarding ad blocking .
According to one of the software companies , trying to circumvent ad blocking is a &quot; cat and mouse game &quot; for companies that make money from online advertising .
On Thursday , just two days after Facebook announced that it would block ad blocking on its desktop , Adblock Plus published a blog post announcing that users could update their program filters to block ads on the social network again .
On Tuesday , Facebook announced that its desktop page would change the encoding of its advertisements to make it more difficult to recognize block ads about which part of the site is advertising .
But Adblock announced that it has found a new way to circumvent the new codes .
In a blog post , Adblock Ben Williams &quot; spokesman wrote that &quot; this kind of back @-@ and @-@ forth battle between the blocking open source community and the bypassers has been going on since ad blockers were invented , &quot; and that Facebook may soon come up with a new solution .
The fact that the world &apos;s largest social media company has joined the fight is a strong indication of how worrying ad blockers have become for the industry .
Worldwide , according to a study last year by Pagefair and Adobe , around 200 million people use ad blockers , almost four times as much in 2013 .
With 1.03 billion active users accessing Facebook every day via their mobile devices , mobile advertising accounts for 84 percent of advertising revenue for Facebook .
The company is targeting ad blockers on desktop PCs , as mobile ad blockers have no effect on Facebook &apos;s mobile app for the social network and instagram , a spokesperson said .
Advertising on desktop PCs accounts for enough revenue to make Facebook consider it worthwhile to invest in such a move .
On Tuesday , Facebook announced that it would update its ad preference tool to give people more control over advertising targeted at them .
On Thursday , Facebook claimed that Adblock &apos;s new filters were worrying because they would also block non @-@ advertising content on the site .
&quot; For users , this is not a positive experience , so we plan to address the issue , &quot; said a Facebook spokesman in an email message .
Ad blocking is a blunt tool , which is why we have instead focused on developer tools such as Ad Preferences to put more control in people &apos;s hands .
