Sun was also at the center of a dispute with Australian Mack Horton .
&quot; I have no time and no respect for doping fraudsters , &quot; he said .
Sun had been tested positively for the Stimulans Trimetazidin in the 2014 Chinese Championships , but only had to serve a three @-@ month suspension .
Data theft : So perfidious hackers extort their ransom .
Programmers of blackmail malware are currently attacking companies in a targeted manner - and are succeeding .
According to a recent survey by malware defence specialists Malwarebytes of 540 companies in North America , the United Kingdom and Germany , 40 percent of the companies surveyed have been victims of blackmail attacks at least once , sometimes several times , in the past 12 months .
In Germany , almost 20 % of companies have already been the target of ransomware blackmail .
Forty per cent of the victims willingly paid the ransoms demanded of the perpetrators in order to be able to reuse the attacked systems and data .
According to Malwarebytes &apos; observations , the perpetrators are increasingly specializing in their blackmail software for attacks on corporate networks .
If they succeed , the potential ransom is much higher than that of private users .
&quot; We are currently witnessing a frighteningly rapid evolution of malware , &quot; explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski in conversation with the &quot; world . &quot;
In 2008 , most malware programs were still designed to send advertising .
Then the perpetrators discovered blackmail software for themselves .
First , private users were targeted , but the shift to corporate attacks has been alarmingly rapid in recent months .
Ransomware works according to a simple pattern : Once active on a victim &apos;s computer , it searches specifically for recently modified files such as Word , Excel or database files , as well as archives of images and videos .
These files encrypt the Ransomware and delete the originals permanently .
The software then presents the blackmailer &apos;s demands .
In order to get the final key code to the files , victims have to transfer money - usually in the form of the crypto currency Bitcoin .
But where the personal photo database is at stake for private users , companies are dealing with sensitive customer data or project databases , without which production will stop .
Correspondingly , when Ransomware strikes , the damage is higher .
22 percent of the German companies affected reported losses in sales due to Ransomware , 13 percent even had to suspend their business completely , in one case people were in danger of dying .
Hospitals in Germany have repeatedly been the victims of attacks , the patients of which may be at acute risk from the loss of medical records .
&quot; We always say to the victims : don &apos;t pay , you &apos;re just promoting the problem , &quot; Kleczynski explains .
But 80 @-@ 90 % of the firms that pay get their data back .
Managers find it difficult to reject the perpetrators &quot; demands in the face of operational standstill .
The hackers , in turn , know this and try their best to build a good reputation .
In a recent study , the security researchers at F @-@ Secure have examined the user interface and the contact with the blackmailers and conclude that the perpetrators are indeed trying to establish some sort of customer service in order to raise more money .
They explain to their victims via chat how to pay by bitcoin , set up free @-@ to @-@ access support websites or decrypt example files for free .
And if individuals are redeemed after paying a few hundred euros , companies sometimes have to negotiate hard and pay five @-@ digit sums to get their data back unencrypted .
With the potential for high and relatively risk @-@ free profits from ransomware blackmail , hackers are becoming more professional and sharing the work , security expert Chester Wisniewski of anti @-@ virus Sophos explains : &quot; A single person can write a ransomware about a week . &quot;
However , it is more likely to be three or four people .
The programmers then sell their malicious software in the form of a set of software modules to the actual blackmailers .
The previous malware kits were created by buying the malware itself , advice and additional tools for a one @-@ time fixed price of between 1000 and 10,000 dollars .
&quot; It comes with a customization tool so you can modify smaller configurations , appearance and branding , &quot; says Wisniewski .
The blackmailers then seek out more hackers to spread the newly bought software among the victims .
We live in a service economy .
So you log into one of the underground forums , buy the set from a criminal and ask another to install the software on as many PCs as possible .
The payment is made per infected computer .
&quot; Criminals usually then hire spammers to distribute it , &quot; Wisniewski explains .
The risk of Ransomware is now well @-@ known among many companies that make their data more secure .
More than 50 percent of companies IT managers in the Malwarebytes survey trust they can ward off Ransomware with file back @-@ ups and scanner software .
Accordingly , the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies .
&quot; When data encryption alone is no longer a sufficient threat to successful capture , the perpetrators instead threaten to publish sensitive data such as customer lists or price calculations , &quot; explains Malwarebytes Chairman Marcin Kleczynski .
Depending on the type of data , the potential for damage is thus many times higher than before .
The perpetrators could also target completely new targets on the Internet of Things in the future .
At the hacker conference Defcon , security researchers demonstrated how they could gain control of a thermostat connected to the Internet .
In the middle of winter , unlocking such a blocked heating system may well be worth ransom to some victims .
If the perpetrators then block an entire production line in a factory instead of the heating in future , Ransomware could also become an issue in industry 4.0 .
One for all cases
HONDA HR @-@ V is flexible and suitable for everyday use .
Honda wants to pack everything in the small HR @-@ V : a little SUV , a little coupé and even the versatility of a minivan .
Sounds rather overloaded , but the HR @-@ V , which was constructed on the same new platform as the new jazz , actually proves to be extremely flexible in everyday life .
Although the HR @-@ V , which is only 1.60m high , seems rather small , passengers have a lot of space in both the front row and the rear , as it does not appear tight at any point .
The materials of the interior are well finished and have a pleasant effect , only the cockpit upper side falls off somewhat .
The HR @-@ V is more versatile than comparable vehicles when it comes to storage space .
Not only is there a trunk of 453 l for upright backrests and 1026 l for folded backrests , but there is also the Magic Seats .
This is less magical than it sounds : the seats of the rear bench can be folded up like cinema chairs , providing storage space that is 1.24 m high from the floor to the ceiling .
The boot is easy to load , although the 650 mm loading height is slightly higher than that of the comparable Peugeot 2008 .
Thanks to the torque of up to 300 Nm , the tested 1.6 l diesel engine with 88 kW / 120 hp accelerates the HR @-@ V very powerfully at wide engine speeds .
He is , however , likely to do his job a little more quietly .
Everyday consumption of 4.7 l / 100 km is pleasant .
There is also another engine : a 1.5 l gasoline engine with 96 kW / 130 hp .
All @-@ wheel drive is not offered .
The driving behaviour is balanced , a good compromise between dynamics and comfort .
However , the steering should be a little more direct .
The equipment in the tested top version &quot; Executive &quot; leaves nothing to be desired .
Safety systems include the City Emergency Brake Assistant ( working up to speed 32 ) , collision warning system and lane departure warning system .
The collision warning is sometimes irritating because it evaluates many obstacles during moving as &quot; approaching objects . &quot;
The remote light assistant works very reliable .
And the intelligent tempo controller reacts to traffic sign recognition and reduces the speed if necessary .
But full connectivity is only available for the top @-@ of @-@ the @-@ line features : 7 @-@ inch touch screen , navigators , app integration and more .
Two USB connectors and one HDMI connector lie under the armrest and are therefore somewhat cumbersome to reach .
The around EUR 29000 for the well @-@ equipped top diesel is fine .
Anyone who does not want to invest so much will receive the petrol from EUR 20000 and the diesel from EUR 23000 .
The engines meet the Euro 6 emission standard .
With the HR @-@ V , Honda offers a versatile and everyday car .
Airline is not liable : crash on passenger bridge
An airline is not liable for the fall of a passenger on the passenger bridge .
The Düsseldorf Higher Regional Court ( Administrative Court ) argued that liability could only be envisaged in the event of dangers typical of air transport ( Case No 18 U 124 / 14 ) .
The plaintiff had broken a knee disc when he fell .
However , the accident could have happened anywhere - it was a general risk to life , the court said .
The airline did not have to pay compensation to the man .
Case of illness : When will the organizer pay ?
Sick holidaymakers only get money back after their journey if the cause of the disease is undoubtedly to be found in the hotel .
However , this is only the case if more than 10 % of guests have been shown to have the same symptoms .
In the case in question , a family suffered from diarrhea and vomiting on the second day of their holiday in Turkey .
She spent almost the entire holiday in the room .
The holidaymakers attributed their illness to a faulty sewage plant that had allegedly polluted the sea water .
The family felt that the trip was thus flawed - and sued the organizer .
In court , the plaintiffs did not succeed .
It is true that the sewage treatment plant was defective .
But the organizer did not learn about it until shortly before the plaintiff left .
Until then , he had to assume that the seawater was in order .
So he did not violate his duty to provide information , the ruling went .
Especially as no contamination was found in the samples of water .
The illness of several hotel guests - possibly due to inter @-@ contagion - is part of the general life risk .
Of 691 guests , only 38 were ill .
