Relaxing Night : Tips Against Sleep Disorder
In the evening you go around eternally , awake for hours at night , in the morning you can &apos;t think of sleep any more , long before the alarm bell rings .
This is far from relaxing .
After all , such problems are in good company : according to the Robert Koch Institute , about a quarter of adults have sleep disorders , and more than 10 % often or permanently feel that their sleep is not recovering .
How do sleep problems or sleep disorders express themselves ?
According to Hans @-@ Günter Weeß , member of the Executive Board of the German Society for Sleep Restoration and Sleep Medicine , there are several forms of sleep disturbances and they may be based on many different causes .
However , what is commonly understood by this term is insulin , that is , a disturbance of sleep and sleep .
According to Jens Wagenknecht , member of the board of directors of the German Family Medical Association with practice in Varel in Lower Saxony , sleeping is regarded by many as unsatisfactory or inadequate .
What is behind sleep disorders ?
The causes of sleep disorders are complex .
Behind this , there may be organic , psychological or behavioural factors , but also medication .
Often sleep disorders are the expression of another disorder .
&quot; Wake up very early is common , especially in a depression , &quot; says Weeß .
And it may be that different factors are interdependent .
For example , if you have an intervertebral disc accident , you can lie down badly , wake up every two to three hours , and perhaps begin to ponder everyday problems and worries , Weeß gives an example .
This causes tension , and sleep is no longer possible .
When should I go to the doctor with sleep disorders ?
Those who don &apos;t sleep well for at least three nights a week over a period of one month and are impaired during the day should go to the doctor , guesses Weeß .
The impairment can be quite different : you are knocked off , tired , sleepless , have difficulty with your attention and concentration , are easily irritable , have mood swings or have physical complaints such as stomach or headache .
To alleviate the sleep disturbance , it is important to find out its causes .
Changes in behaviour , cognitive behavioural therapy or medicines - classical sleeping pills are only possible in exceptional cases and for a maximum of two weeks - are among the treatment options .
According to Prof. Ingo Fietze , head of the interdisciplinary sleep medicine centre of the Charité Universitätsmedizin Berlin , there are hardly any established sleep doctors in Germany .
In case of sleep problems , consult your family doctor first , Weeß advises .
He can use examinations to determine whether the problems have a physical cause .
Who should go to the dormitory , and what happens there ?
For the examination in the sleep laboratory , physicians recommend , for example , snoring with respirators , pathological fatigue , sleepers , or failure to find the cause of a sleep disturbance , explains Fietze .
There is really no need to prepare for the investigation .
The day should be spent normally .
&quot; Just don &apos;t take a nap , &quot; says Fietze .
After cabling , you go to bed at your normal time .
In addition to the electrodes on the body , you wear nose glasses , a chest strap and a sensing device on your finger .
A camera also records the sleeping person on the ceiling .
How can those affected get a grip on the problems ?
There are quite a few adjustment screws on which you can attach for a better sleep .
What counts is that regular periods of sleep and getting up , not lying in bed too long , not sleeping during the day , not watching television to fall asleep , avoiding alcohol and not looking at the clock at night - because then you start counting straight away , which is not at all helpful .
