Airport : gang of baggage thieves arrested
Professional Rogues at Düsseldorf Airport
Civic investigators from the Düsseldorf police arrested two women and two men aged between 50 and 61 on Thursday .
As a gang , the suspects had committed a number of bag and baggage theft .
At around 9.30 p.m. , civilian officials re @-@ identified a gang known to police from past theft offences in the Düsseldorf airport area .
The two women and two men had committed a number of offences since mid @-@ July of this year and had acted in a joint , division of labour and particularly professional manner .
Specialists in Commissioner 34 can prove four acts to the thieves who had entered Germany specifically to commit crimes .
They had captured a total of more than 15,000 euros .
Old buildings , a few linden trees , a few more cobblestones in between : Rigaer Strasse in Berlin @-@ Friedrichshain doesn &apos;t look that way at first glance , but the police rank it among the &quot; dangerous places &quot; of the city .
Walking along the road from east to west , you will pass by playgrounds , a newly painted kindergarten and a organic shop .
Someone has sprayed &quot; ugly ! &quot; on the facade of a grey house .
Opposite a lidl , which is soon to be demolished , a house with high windows and 133 new rental apartments is already being built .
In the last few weeks , however , articles about this &quot; trendy district , &quot; as the responsible real estate company Friedrichshain calls it , have been featured primarily with burning cars .
The reason for this is the number 94 : Once it was occupied , now the residents have lease contracts , but on the ground floor there are still rooms occupied and are used for events .
In particular , the Berlin interior senator Henkel had , on several occasions since the beginning of the year , called for a tough police approach to the project , calling the area a &quot; no go zone &quot; for policemen and 94 a starting point for autonomous violence .
After clearing the ground floor premises , the carcass smiths , with 300 police officers on 22 June , the police patrolled , for three weeks , according to official reports , with between 30 and 40 officials and three team cars on the ground , closed off parts of the street and stopped visitors from entering the house at number 94 .
Meanwhile , construction workers renovated the rooms on behalf of unknown house owners .
On 13 July , a Berlin administrative court ruled that the eviction had been illegal , and the day after , the police and construction workers withdrew , cheering from sympathisers and residents .
This summer afternoon the street is peaceful : parents are walking with children , people are sitting in the sun on the sidewalk in front of the houses , others are talking before late .
A primary school and nursery schools are located in the immediate vicinity of the house projects .
Left @-@ wing violence is not the main concern of many residents : Kerstin Neugebauer , who has lived in the neighbourhood since 1999 , and Jana * , who is bringing up three children here , are particularly annoyed by the police presence .
Together with the inhabitants of the house projects , they share the concern about rising rents and gentrification .
It does not sound like a Kiev which , for the most part , wanted police protection from vandalising left @-@ wingers .
The gap that the Berlin Interior Senator and the police are opening between squatters and their neighbours obviously does not exist like this .
Friedrichshain in East Berlin was actually a traditional working @-@ class district , which still has a low average income and a high risk of poverty compared to the rest of the city .
Even squatting and the resulting residential projects have long been part of Kiev : in 1990 , numerous houses in the former GDR were occupied , including almost the entire Mainzer Strasse near the Rigaer .
While the Mainz population had been evicted in a veritable street battle with large numbers of police , many of the projects in the Rigaer were legalised and are still inhabited today by the people they occupied 26 years ago .
At the same time , the district has increasingly become a magnet for tourists and election @-@ makers from all over the world : residents of GDR times and former squatters are now sharing their neighbourhood .
This is also noticeable in the rents , which have risen by almost 60 percent since 2009 for new rents .
Many of the new buildings in the Rigaer are under attack as symbols of this development : they can be recognised by discarded windows or freshly painted facades , which have been covered with paint bags .
No other street has been mentioned so often this year , along with the words &apos; left @-@ wing autonomous violence &apos; .
One reason that not all neighbours see this as a problem may be that they are not necessarily affected by crime : crimes such as bodily injury , according to statistics , are directed almost exclusively at police officers .
The largest proportion of crimes is property damage , which tends to affect new buildings and newly renovated houses more .
For Kerstin Neugebauer , who has lived for 17 years in a rented house next to the controversial 94 , there can be no question of insecurity .
As far as acts of violence are concerned , it is reassuring : the people of 94 are their neighbours , and they certainly were not .
The famous burning cars have also not existed in the Rigaer for a long time .
For the architect studied , her street is not a criminal focal point , on the contrary : &quot; Here you help each other , live together on the street and get more from each other than anywhere else . &quot;
Neugebauer has deliberately moved into the Rigaer Straße - and has remained so .
That is why it was so important to her that the residents get back their streets : from the police , politics and the media , all of whom suddenly claimed sovereignty over the district in July .
In the eyes of both residents and newcomers , however , the road continues to be taken away from them : through faceless new buildings in former building gaps that are displacing the old inhabitants .
&quot; These are , after all , condominiums that are not of interest to many people here - rather people who are not so well @-@ heeled live here , &quot; she says .
&apos;I absolutely cannot condone violence and destruction . &apos;
But what should you do if you never hear someone ?
There is frustration on all sides , including the police and the residents .
Kerstin Neugebauer has little sympathy for those drawn in who resent colour bombs : the house projects and the left @-@ wing scene were part of the Kiez .
Anyone who goes there should be aware of this - just as someone who goes to a pub district can complain badly about noise there .
All persons presented with first names only have asked not to be named with their real names .
Urbach : Annika Deuschle is the new refugee representative
Annika Deuschle is the contact person regarding integration and organizer .
She is also a local social worker .
Since July , Annika Deuschle has been the refugee representative for Urbach .
The social education teacher supports the administration team around Achim Grockenberger .
She sees herself as the point of contact for all the actors : refugees , the working group on aid for refugees , the administration , the authorities and anyone else involved .
Regine Kunde vom Arbeitskreis hints that the volunteers are more than thankful that Deuschle is now here , the icy Wollmilchsau , which has a problem above all .
For example , some people meant - not so much mocking , but aimed at the multitude of tasks that they wanted - when the administration wanted to put the post out to tender .
There was a need for an administrator with a talent for languages and people , combined with many years of experience in the social work sector , to create an egg @-@ laying wool dairy .
But administrative work is not their central area , says Annika Deuschle .
Above all , it is about organisation , working with people on the ground and also behind the scenes , and networking .
The 31 @-@ year @-@ old has been with us for about six weeks .
It has a 50 % post limited to three years .
&quot; It was high time , &quot; says Regine Kunde , that Annika Deuschle supports honest and full @-@ time actors .
There are big and small problems , organisational , human and communication problems .
New containers will soon be added to Wasenstraße .
For some time now , it has been a serious problem to find housing for the resettled refugees who have been recognised .
The local authorities are responsible for the provision of connecting accommodation .
They must house the refugees in their own or rented housing .
The costs of the construction , rent or renovation of these accommodation units must be borne by the local authorities themselves .
Responsibility changes from County Council office to local authority and job centre .
Problem : There are available properties , but not every landlord wants to offer their apartment .
The search has been very difficult for some time .
The de facto administration cannot find private homes .
According to Deuschle , it has not worked so far , relying on private apartments .
That is why we need to create communal housing , as they say .
So new containers will soon be placed in the Wasenstraße .
But housing is not enough .
Perspective is the key word , Regine Kunde and Annika Deuschle agree .
In addition to permanent residence , these are internships , training places , school places , one @-@ euro jobs and temporary jobs for refugees and migrants that need to be thought up or set up .
&quot; More places would be good , &quot; reports Regine Kunde .
Many work at the construction farm or help caretakers , do charitable work - and this is motivated and very well done , as Annika Deuschle reports .
It hopes that the work for the community will lead to a positive external impact .
That is &quot; not an employment therapy . &quot;
But work does not just mean work .
The day needs a fixed structure , say Deuschle and customer .
People would have to develop a sense of belonging .
So there is a need for activities such as sports , contacts with locals and , above all , language courses .
Professional courses are rare .
So the administration and voluntary workers are stepping in here too .
It is vital that the refugees get the feeling that they are wanted and welcome in Germany .
The long duration of the proceedings is a problem .
They must explain to the refugees that it is taking time and that they can usefully bridge the time gap , for example with language courses .
Anyone who at some point has the feeling that they cannot help anyone in Urbach is not allowed to work and is useless will never integrate .
The clear majority is motivated .
But there are also problems , says customer honestly , &quot; people with whom nothing is possible . &quot; The work of Deuschle and customer is therefore always to motivate others .
All this is a mammoth task in itself .
One difficult question : are they afraid of radicalization , even in a small community like Urbach , following recent events ?
&quot; No , &quot; Regine Kunde clearly says , &quot; which some may call naive . &quot; But she cannot and will not rule out a residual risk .
However , the helpers are already aware of this .
These incidents are also an issue for the refugees .
They would fear that the perpetrators of the attacks would bring them completely into discredit .
&quot; They want to show that they have nothing to do with it , &quot; says Regine Kunde .
Many would like to stay in Urbach .
So primary and voluntary workers must look for activities on the ground and in the region .
They always keep in mind that a new shock to refugees and migrants could soon arrive in Urbach .
Does Germany need a cap ?
Politicians are afraid to answer this question clearly .
It is actually unfair to put them on the ground .
&quot; We have not yet arrived in Urbach where we would like to go , &quot; says Annika Deuschle .
No new refugees , that would ease the situation .
Regine Kunde also makes it clear that the Urbacher people are already busy integrating the existing people in a sensible way .
That currently amounts to around 100 people , mostly young men .
But when people are in need , they must be helped , both women agree .
The political situation in the world is so complicated , there are no easy answers .
Chimney Village : Helicopter Intruders Wanted
The police helicopter took off from various areas for about an hour , without success .
At about 8.50 a.m. on Friday morning , two unknown men violently entered an apartment in a multi @-@ family house in the Lindenweg .
The resident surprised the two and beat the dodgy into flight .
The two men were about 1.65 to 1.70 meters tall , probably masked , wearing both bluejeans and black hooded pulses .
They fled towards the city centre .
The police used several strip crews as well as a police helicopter to investigate .
The investigation went without success .
The strangers may have been noticed during their flight from the apartment or close to it .
Baden @-@ Württemberg : Police investigate after the rocker attack on snack
After an attack on an Ulm snack , the police are investigating six Rockermilieu suspects for a serious breach of the country peace .
On Friday , the police reported that evidence and drugs had been seized during house searches .
According to the police , around 20 masked men from a rocker @-@ like group had thrown bottles and stones against the shop window of a snack in July .
They then allegedly attacked two guests and slightly injured one .
After that , they fled .
Damage to the snack bar and the adjacent building amounted to EUR 10 000 .
According to the investigators , this is a dispute in the Ulm Rockermilieu between a Kurdish gang and a Turkish gang .
Thuringia : Zeiss Meditec Getting closer to Sales Billion
A high demand for medical technology in Asia has boosted Carl Zeiss Meditec &apos;s sales .
In the first nine months of the fiscal year , which began in October , Group revenues increased by 6.7 percent to EUR 798.6 million , as reported by the publicly traded company in Jena on Friday .
The Asian business grew disproportionately by 17.1 percent .
Profits before interest and taxes increased from EUR 89.5 million to EUR 110.5 million according to the interim balance sheet .
The Board of Management confirmed that the Jenaer Medical Technology Group intends to exceed the sales mark of one billion euros this fiscal year .
Zeiss Meditec produces equipment and equipment for medical practices and clinics .
The company , which is part of the optical and electronics group Carl Zeiss ( Oberkochen ) , employs nearly 3,000 people .
